'''Badara Tittha Vihara''' (also '''Badaratittha''', '''Padaratittha'''<ref name=hopl>{{cite book|last=Bimala Churn Law|title=History of Pali Literature|year=1933|publisher=Kegan, Paul, Trench, Trubner and Co., Ltd.|location=London|url=https://archive.org/details/ahistoryofpalili035454mbp}}</ref> ) is the name of an historic [[Theravada]] [[Buddhist]] ''[[vihara]]'' in what is now the modern [[Tamil Nadu]] state of [[India]].

==In the Gandhavamsa==
Badaratittha is known to us from the ''[[Gandhavamsa]]'' (or ''[[Cullagandhavamsa]]''), a 17th-century ''[[Pali]]'' work by ''[[Nandapanna|Nandapa√±√±a]]'' that recounts post-canonical Pali books written in [[Burma]] and [[Ceylon]].  

The ''Gandhavamsa'' states that Badara Tittha Vihara was the dwelling place of ''[[Dhammapala|ƒÄcariya DhammapƒÅla]]'', an early Theravadin commentator from [[Kanchipuram]].

