The '''Curia Calabra''' was a religious station or ''[[Glossary of ancient Roman religion#templum|templum]]'' used for the ritual observation of the [[new moon]] in [[ancient Rome]]. Although its exact location is unclear, it was most likely a roofless enclosure in front of an augural hut ''([[Glossary of ancient Roman religion#auguraculum|auguraculum]])'', on the southwest flank of the ''[[Area Capitolina]]'', the precinct of [[Temple of Capitoline Jupiter]]. [[Servius]] identifies the Curia Calabra with a ''[[Casa Romuli]]'' ("Hut of [[Romulus]]") on the [[Capitoline Hill|Capitoline]],<ref>[[Servius]], note to ''[[Aeneid]]'' 8.654.</ref> but [[Macrobius]] implies that it was adjacent to the ''Casa''.<ref>[[Macrobius]], ''Saturnalia'' 1.15.10, 19.</ref>
The [[Roman calendar]] was originally [[lunar calendar|lunar]]. On the [[Kalends]] or first day of each month, the [[pontifex minor]] occupied the Curia Calabra to await the sighting of the new moon. The [[Rex Sacrificulus]] and the pontifex then carried out a ''[[Glossary of ancient Roman religion#res divinae|res divina]]'' (religious service) and sacrifice in honor of [[Juno (mythology)|Juno]], and the Roman people were called to assembly ''(in [[comitia calata]])''. Like ''calata'', the name ''Calabra'' probably derives from ''calare'', "to summon" or "proclaim".<ref>[[Varro]], ''De lingua latina'' 6.27; Macrobius, ''Saturnalia'' 1.15.10‚Äì19.</ref>
==Sources== * Lawrence Richardson, ''A New Topographical Dictionary of Ancient Rome'' (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1992), p.&nbsp;102.
