{{Refimprove|date=October 2007}}[[Image:Laupheim Friedrich Adler.JPG|thumb|right|Birthplace of Friedrich Adler in Laupheim]] [[Image:Friedrich-Adler-2.jpg|thumb|right|Art deco lamp]] '''Friedrich Adler''' (29 April 1878 ‚Äì ca. 11 July 1942) was a [[Germany|German]] [[academia|academic]], [[artist]] and [[designer]]. He was especially renowned for his accomplishments in designing metalwork in the [[Art nouveau]] and [[Art deco]] styles; he was also the first designer to use [[bakelite]].
Adler was born in [[Laupheim]]; his birthplace is now the ''Caf√© Hermes'', an Art nouveau building in the style of the late [[Italian Renaissance]].<ref>{{Cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | title = The Jewish Past of Laupheim: The Adler Family | work = | publisher = | url = http://www.culturespace.de/laupheim/english/adler.htm | doi = | accessdate = 2010-03-28 }}</ref>
From 1894 to 1897, he studied under [[Hermann Obrist]] and [[Wilhelm von Debschitz]], in whose [[wikt:atelier|atelier]] he also taught from 1904 to 1907, at the School for [[Applied Art]] in [[Munich]]. From 1907 to 1933, he taught at the [[Hochschule f√ºr bildende K√ºnste Hamburg|School for Applied Art in Hamburg]]. In between, he also directed the mastery lessons in [[Nuremberg]], and was busy designing pieces in applied art for over fifty clients.
On 11 July 1942 Adler, who was [[Jew]]ish, was deported to the [[extermination camp]] [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]], where, judged too old to work, he was killed soon afterwards. There is a [[stolperstein]] in his memory at his last place of employment in Hamburg.
