'''Gamigin''' is the fourth [[Goetia|Goetic]] [[demon]] described in [[the Lesser Key of Solomon]] (referred to in the Crowley/Mathers edition as '''Samigina'''), and (as '''Gamygyn''') forty-sixth in the [[Pseudomonarchia Daemonum]], in both works as a marquis who initially takes the form of a small horse before transforming into a hoarse-voiced human. The Lesser Key of Solomon merely leaves his duties at teaching liberal arts and giving accounts of souls that died in sin.<ref>Lemegeton Clavicula Salomonis: The Lesser Key of Solomon, Detailing the Ceremonial Art of Commanding Spirits Both Good and Evil; ed. Joseph H. Peterson; Weiser Books, Maine; 2001. p.7-10</ref>  

The Pseudomonarchia Daemonum, [[Thomas Rudd]]'s variant of the Ars Goetia, and the [[Dictionnaire Infernal]] go into more detail, with Gamigin forcing the souls of those who drowned into "airy bodies" to answer questions in either, with Weyer and de Plancy further claiming that Gamigan can do likewise for souls "which dwell in [[Purgatory|purgatorie]] (which is called Cartagra, that is, affliction of soules)".<ref>Pseudomonarchia Daemonum (Liber officiorum spirituum); Johann Weyer, ed. Joseph Peterson; 2000. Available online at [http://www.esotericarchives.com/solomon/weyer.htm Esoteric Archives]. [http://www.esotericarchives.com/solomon/weyer.htm#par40 par 40-49]</ref><ref>The Goetia of Dr Rudd; Thomas Rudd, Ed. Stephen Skinner & David Rankine; 2007, Golden Hoard Press. p.100-109</ref><ref>Dictionnaire infernal: ou R√©pertoire universel des √™tres, des personnages, Jacques Collin de Plancy, 1853, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ng8JAAAAQAAJ&dq=intitle%3ADictionnaire%20intitle%3AInfernal&lr&num=100&as_brr=1&pg=PA5#v=onepage&q&f=false available on Google Books] p.230-239</ref> According to Rudd, Gamigin is opposed by the [[Shemhamphorasch]] angel Ieuiah.<ref>Rudd, ed. Skinner & Rankine, p.366-376</ref>

