'''John Hickes''' or '''Hicks''' (1633‚Äì1685), was an English nonconformist minister.

Hickes was the brother of [[George Hickes (divine)|George Hickes]], born at Moorhouse, [[Kirby Wiske]], [[North Riding of Yorkshire]]. He was a student and then fellow of [[Trinity College, Dublin]]. He was ejected from [[Saltash]], [[Cornwall]] after the [[Uniformity Act of 1662]].<ref name="DNB">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Hickes, John|volume=26}}</ref>

Hickes presented a petition to [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] in favour of [[nonconformists]]. Under [[James II of England|James II]] he joined the [[Duke of Monmouth's Rebellion]] in 1685 and was sheltered by [[Alice Lisle]]. He was tried and executed at [[Taunton]].<ref name="DNB"/>

