'''Luis Bu√±uel Portol√©s''' ({{IPA-es|Ààlwis Œ≤uÀà…≤wel po…ætoÀàles}}; 22 February 1900 ‚Äì 29 July 1983) was a Spanish [[filmmaker]] who worked in Spain, Mexico and France.<ref name="Encyclop√¶dia Britannica">{{cite web|last=Kyrou|first=Ado|title=Luis Bu√±uel|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Luis-Bunuel|website=Encyclop√¶dia Britannica|publisher=Encyclop√¶dia Britannica, Inc.|accessdate=9 October 2017}}</ref>
When Luis Bu√±uel died at age 83, his [[obituary]] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' called him "an [[iconoclast]], moralist, and revolutionary who was a leader of [[avant-garde]] [[surrealism]] in his youth and a dominant international movie director half a century later".<ref>{{cite news|last=Flint|first=Peter B.|title=Luis Bu√±uel Dies at 83; Filmmaker for 50 Years|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/07/30/obituaries/luis-bunuel-dies-at-83-film-maker-for-50-years.html|accessdate=6 August 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=30 July 1983}}</ref> His first picture, ''[[Un Chien Andalou]]''‚Äîmade in the [[silent film|silent era]]‚Äîwas called "the most famous short film ever made" by critic [[Roger Ebert]],<ref name=ebert>{{cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=Un Chien Andalou Movie Review (1928)|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-un-chien-andalou-1928|work=Great Movies: The First 100|publisher=RogerEbert.com|accessdate=9 October 2017|date=16 April 2000}}</ref> and his last film, ''[[That Obscure Object of Desire]]''‚Äîmade 48 years later‚Äîwon him Best Director awards from the [[National Board of Review]] and the [[National Society of Film Critics]].<ref name="Ramirez Berg">{{cite web|url=http://www.austinfilm.org/essential-cinema/program-notes-that-obscure-object-of-desire |title=Program Notes: THAT OBSCURE OBJECT OF DESIRE |last=Berg |first=Charles Ram√≠rez |publisher=Austin Film Society |accessdate=9 October 2017 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610201718/http://www.austinfilm.org/essential-cinema/program-notes-that-obscure-object-of-desire |archivedate=10 June 2015 |df= }}</ref> Writer [[Octavio Paz]] called Bu√±uel's work "the marriage of the film image to the poetic image, creating a new reality...scandalous and subversive".<ref name=paz>{{cite book|last=Paz|first=Octavio|title=On Poets and Others|year=1986|publisher=Arcade Publishing|location=New York|isbn=978-1-55970-139-6|pages=152|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qoiEQ4FiuFsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>
Often associated with the [[surrealist movement]] of the 1920s, Bu√±uel created films from the 1920s through the 1970s. His work spans two continents, three languages, and an array of genres, including [[experimental film]], [[Documentary film|documentary]], [[Melodrama#Film|melodrama]], [[satire]], [[Musical film|musical]], [[Sex in film|erotica]], [[Comedy film|comedy]], [[Romance film|romance]], [[costume drama]]s, [[Fantasy film|fantasy]], [[crime film]], [[Adventure film|adventure]], and [[Western (genre)#Film|western]]. Despite this variety, filmmaker [[John Huston]] believed that, regardless of genre, a Bu√±uel film is so distinctive as to be instantly recognizable,<ref>{{cite book|last=Sinyard|first=Neil|title="The Discreet Charm of Houston and Bu√±uel: Notes on a Cinematic Odd Couple", in John Huston: Essays on a Restless Director, ed. Tony Tracy and Roddy Flynn|year=2010|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson NC|isbn=978-0-7864-5853-0|pages=73|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xhfl7DdYTMQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> or, as [[Ingmar Bergman]] put it, "Bu√±uel nearly always made Bu√±uel films".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bergmanorama.webs.com/bergman_on_directors.htm |title=Commentary: Bergman on Filmmakers |publisher=Berganorama |accessdate=9 October 2017 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090624023319/http://bergmanorama.webs.com/bergman_on_directors.htm |archivedate=24 June 2009 |df= }}</ref>
Six of Bu√±uel's films are included in ''[[Sight & Sound]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 2012 critics' poll of the top 250 films of all time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Critics' Top 250 Films |url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/sightandsoundpolls/2012/critics |website=Sight and Sound |publisher=British Film Institute |accessdate=18 August 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026034922/http://explore.bfi.org.uk/sightandsoundpolls/2012/critics |archivedate=26 October 2013 |df= }}</ref> Fifteen of his films are included in the ''They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?'' list of the 1,000 greatest films of all time, for which he ranks second only to [[Jean-Luc Godard]], with sixteen,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_all1000films_table.php|title=The 1,000 Greatest Films|publisher=They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?}}</ref> and he ranks number 13 on their list of the top 250 directors.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Top 250 Directors|url=http://www.theyshootpictures.com/gf1000_top250directors.htm|publisher=They Shoot Pictures, Don't They?|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref>
==Early years== [[File:Vista parcial de Calanda. Foto Jos√© Antonio Bielsa.JPG|thumb|right|Calanda, Spain|[[Calanda, Spain|Calanda]], Spain]] Bu√±uel was born in [[Calanda, Spain|Calanda]], a small town in the [[Teruel (province)|province of Teruel]], in the [[Aragon]] region of Spain, to Leonardo Bu√±uel, the cultivated scion of an established Aragonese family, and Mar√≠a Portol√©s, many years younger than her husband, with wealth and family connections of her own.<ref name=Alcala>{{cite book|last=Alcal√°|first=Manuel|title=Bu√±uel (Cine e ideologia)|year=1973|publisher=Edicusa|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-229-0101-3}}</ref>{{rp|pp.16‚Äì17}} He would later describe his birthplace by saying that in Calanda, "the [[Middle Ages]] lasted until [[World War&nbsp;I]]".<ref>Bu√±uel, Luis. ''My Last Sigh''. Trans. Abigail Israel. Minneapolis: [[University of Minnesota Press]], 2003. {{ISBN|0-8166-4387-3}}. page 8.</ref> The oldest of seven children, Luis had two brothers, Alfonso and Leonardo, and four sisters: Alicia, Concepci√≥n, Margarita and Mar√≠a.<ref name=schwarze>{{cite book|last=Schwarze|first=Michael|title=Luis Bu√±uel|year=1988|publisher=Plaza & Janes|location=Barcelona|isbn=978-84-01-45079-2|pages=9}}</ref>
When Bu√±uel was four and a half months old, the family moved to [[Zaragoza]], where they were one of the wealthiest families in town.<ref name=Alcala />{{rp|p.22}} In Zaragoza, Bu√±uel received a strict [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] education at the private Colegio del Salvador.<ref name=Alcala />{{rp|pp.23‚Äì36}} After being kicked and insulted by the study hall proctor before a final exam, Bu√±uel refused to return to the school.<ref name="directors guide" /> He told his mother he had been expelled, which was not true; in fact, he had received the highest marks on his world history exam.<ref>Bu√±uel, Luis. ''My Last Sigh''. Trans. Abigail Israel. Minneapolis: University of Minnesota Press, 2003. {{ISBN|0-8166-4387-3}}. page 30.</ref> Bu√±uel finished the last two years of his high school education at the local public school.<ref name="directors guide">{{cite web|title=Luis Bunuel|url=http://www.greatestdirectors.com/buneul.html|website=The Directors Guide|publisher=Website Creations|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> Even as a child, Bu√±uel was something of a cinematic showman; friends from that period described productions in which Bu√±uel would project shadows on a screen using a [[magic lantern]] and a bedsheet.<ref name="A Proposito de Bunuel">{{cite web|last=Gobierno de Aragon|title=A Proposito de Bunuel ‚Äì Screenplay|url=http://www.american-buddha.com/bunuel.screenplay.htm|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> He also excelled at boxing and playing the violin.<ref name="Encyclop√¶dia Britannica" />
[[File:Salvador Dal√≠ 1939.jpg|thumb|left|[[Salvador Dal√≠]]]]
In his youth, Bu√±uel was deeply religious, serving at Mass and taking Communion every day, until, at the age of 16, he grew disgusted with what he perceived as the illogicality of the Church, along with its power and wealth.<ref name=brandon>{{cite book|last=Brandon|first=Ruth|title=Surreal Lives: The Surrealists 1917‚Äì1945|year=1999|publisher=Macmillan|location=London|isbn=978-0-8021-3727-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9_Z0rVDhNGsC&pg=PA291&lpg=PA291&dq=bunuel+agronomy#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20agronomy}}</ref>{{rp|p.292}}
In 1917, he attended the [[Complutense University of Madrid|University of Madrid]], first studying [[agronomy]] then [[industrial engineering]] and finally switching to [[philosophy]].<ref name="smith celebrities">{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Warren Allen|title=Celebrities in Hell|year=2002|publisher=Barricade Books|location=Fort Lee, NJ|isbn=978-1-56980-214-4|pages=25|url=https://books.google.com/?id=x73FqQgvzgQC&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=luis+bunuel+agronomy#v=onepage&q=luis%20bunuel%20agronomy}}</ref> He developed a very close relationship with painter [[Salvador Dal√≠]] and poet [[Federico Garc√≠a Lorca]], among other important Spanish creative artists living in the [[Residencia de Estudiantes]], with the three friends forming the nucleus of the Spanish Surrealist [[avant-garde]],<ref name=delgado>{{cite book|last=Delgado|first=Manuel and Alice J. Poust|title=Lorca, Bu≈Üuel, Dal√≠: Art and Theory|year=2001|publisher=Associated University Presses|location=Cranbury NJ|isbn=978-0-8387-5508-2|pages=passim|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fOJRnesy3x8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> and becoming known as members of "[[Generation of '27|La Generaci√≥n del 27]]".<ref name=poets.org>{{cite web|title=La Generacion del 27: Dal√≠, Bu√±uel, and Lorca|url=http://www.poets.org/viewmedia.php/prmMID/5944|publisher=Poets.org|accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref> Bu√±uel was especially taken with Lorca, later writing in his autobiography: "We liked each other instantly. Although we seemed to have little in common‚ÄîI was a redneck from Aragon, and he an elegant Andalusian‚Äîwe spent most of our time together... We used to sit on the grass in the evenings behind the Residencia (at that time, there were vast open spaces reaching to the horizon), and he would read me his poems. He read slowly and beautifully, and through him I began to discover a wholly new world."<ref name="my last sigh">{{cite book|last=Bu√±uel|first=Luis|title=My last sigh|year=1983|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-394-52854-0}}</ref>{{rp|p.62}} Bu√±uel's relationship with Dal√≠ was somewhat more troubled, being tinged with jealousy over the growing intimacy between Dal√≠ and Lorca and resentment over Dal√≠'s early success as an artist.<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.300}}
[[File:Lorca (1914).jpg|thumb|right|[[Federico Garc√≠a Lorca]]]]
Since he was 17, he steadily dated the future poet and dramatist [[Concha M√©ndez]], with whom he vacationed every summer at [[San Sebasti√°n]]. He introduced her to his friends at the Residencia as his fianc√©e.<ref name=bellver>{{cite book|last=Bellver|first=Catherine Gullo|title=Absence and Presence: Spanish Women Poets of the Twenties and Thirties|year=2001|publisher=Bucknell University Press|location=Lewisburg, PA|isbn=978-0-8387-5463-4|pages=232}}</ref><ref name=wilcox>{{cite book|last=Wilcox|first=John Chapman|title=Women Poets of Spain, 1860‚Äì1990: Toward a Gynocentric Vision|year=1997|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana and Chicago| isbn=978-0-252-06559-0|pages=125|url=https://books.google.com/?id=i8RlmBiUl68C&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125&dq=concha+mendez+bunuel#v=onepage&q=concha%20mendez%20bunuel}}</ref> After five years, she broke off the relationship, citing Bu√±uel's "insufferable character".<ref name=agonia.net>{{cite web|title=Biografia Concha Mendez Cuesta|url=http://portugues.agonia.net/index.php/author/0028634/index.html|publisher=Agonia.Net|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>
During his student years, Bu√±uel became an accomplished hypnotist. He claimed that once, while calming a hysterical prostitute through [[hypnosis|hypnotic]] suggestion, he inadvertently put one of the several bystanders into a trance as well.<ref name="my last sigh" />{{rp|p.67}} He was often to insist that watching movies was a form of hypnosis: "This kind of cinematographic hypnosis is no doubt due to the darkness of the theatre and to the rapidly changing scenes, lights, and camera movements, which weaken the spectator's critical intelligence and exercise over him a kind of fascination."<ref name="my last sigh" />{{rp|p.69}}
Bu√±uel's interest in films was intensified by a viewing of [[Fritz Lang]]'s ''[[Destiny (1921 film)|Der m√ºde Tod]]'': "I came out of the [[Th√©√¢tre du Vieux-Colombier|Vieux Colombier]] [theater] completely transformed. Images could and did become for me the true means of expression. I decided to devote myself to the cinema".<ref name="Buffalo Film Seminars 1">{{cite web|last=Christian|first=Diane, and Bruce Jackson|title=Luis Bu√±uel That Obscure Object of Desire/ Cet obscur oject du d√©sir 1977|url=http://csac.buffalo.edu/desire.pdf|website=Buffalo Film Seminars|publisher=Market Arcade Film & Arts Center and State University of New York at Buffalo|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref> At age 72, Bu√±uel had not lost his enthusiasm for this film, asking the octogenarian Lang for his autograph.<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.301}}
==Career==
===Early French period (1925‚Äì1930)=== [[File:Jean epstein 1920.jpg|thumb|left|150px|[[Jean Epstein]], Bu√±uel's first film collaborator]] In 1925 Bu√±uel moved to Paris, where he began work as a secretary in an organization called the International Society of Intellectual Cooperation.<ref name="bfi vol 3">{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Paul|title="L'Age d'Or" in British Film Institute Film Classics, Volume 3|year=2003|publisher=Taylor and Francis|location=New York|isbn=978-1-57958-328-6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=V96tee1l2q8C&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&dq=bunuel+intellectual+cooperation#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20intellectual%20cooperation}}</ref>{{rp|p.124}} He also became actively involved in cinema and theater, going to the movies as often as three times a day.<ref name=williams>{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Alan Larson|title=Republic of Images: A History of French Filmmaking|year=1992|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-674-76267-1|pages=152|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ESVZOghoi6kC&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=jean+epstein+luis+bunuel#v=onepage&q=jean%20epstein%20luis%20bunuel}}</ref> Through these interests, he met a number of influential people, including the pianist [[Ricardo Vi√±es]], who was instrumental in securing Bu√±uel's selection as artistic director of the Dutch premiere of [[Manuel de Falla]]'s puppet-opera ''[[El retablo de maese Pedro]]'' in 1926.<ref name=talens>{{cite book|last=Tal√©ns|first=Jenaro|title=The Branded Eye: Bu√±uel's Un Chien Andalou|year=1993|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-2046-3|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5209-5Ai_ZwC&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=bunuel+abel+gance#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20abel%20gance}}</ref>{{rp|p.29}}
He decided to enter the film industry and enrolled in a private film school run by [[Jean Epstein]] and some associates.<ref name=williams /> At that time, Epstein was one of the most celebrated commercial directors working in France, his films being hailed as "the triumph of [[impressionism]] in motion, but also the triumph of the modern spirit".<ref name=sadoul>{{cite book|last=Sadoul|first=Georges|title=Dictionary of Film Makers|year=1972|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley & Los Angeles|isbn=978-0-520-02151-8|pages=77|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PvsZikRu-hAC&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=jean+epstein+reputation#v=onepage&q=jean%20epstein%20reputation}}</ref> Before long, Bu√±uel was working for Epstein as an assistant director on ''[[Mauprat (film)|Mauprat]]'' (1926) and ''[[The Fall of the House of Usher (1928 French film)|La chute de la maison Usher]]'' (1928),<ref name=edwards>{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Gwynne|title=A Companion to Lu√≠s Bu√±uel|year=2005|publisher=Tamesis|location=Woodbridge|isbn=978-1-85566-108-0|url=https://books.google.com/?id=r5_VlQTnbD0C&pg=PA21&lpg=PA21&dq=bunuel+epstein#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20baker}}</ref> and also for [[Mario Nalpas]] on ''La Sir√®ne des Tropiques'' (1927), starring [[Josephine Baker]].<ref name=fandor>{{cite web|title=Siren of the Tropics|url=http://www.fandor.com/films/siren_of_the_tropics|website=fandor|publisher=Our Film Festival, Inc.|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> He appeared on screen in a small part as a smuggler in [[Jacques Feyder]]'s ''[[Carmen (1926 film)|Carmen]]'' (1926).<ref name="brain juice">{{cite web|title=Luis Bu√±uel|url=http://www.brain-juice.com/cgi-bin/show_bio.cgi?p_id=136|website=brain-juice|publisher=Brain-Juice.Com, Inc.|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref>
When Bu√±uel somewhat derisively refused to acquiesce to Epstein's demand that he assist Epstein's mentor, [[Abel Gance]], who was at the time working on the film ''[[Napol√©on (1927 film)|Napol√©on]]'', Epstein dismissed him angrily, saying "How can a little asshole like you dare to talk that way about a great director like Gance?"<ref name=talens />{{rp|p.30}} then added "You seem rather surrealist. Beware of surrealists, they are crazy people."<ref name="de la colina">{{cite book|last=De La Colina|first=Jose|title=Objects of Desire: Conversations with Luis Bunuel|year=1994|publisher=Marsilio Publishers|isbn=978-0-941419-69-7|pages=80}}</ref>
After parting with Epstein, Bu√±uel worked as film critic for ''La Gaceta Literaria'' (1927) and ''Les Cahiers d'Art'' (1928).<ref name=talens />{{rp|p.30}} In the periodicals ''L'Amic de les Arts'' and ''La gaseta de les Arts'', he and Dal√≠ carried on a series of "call and response" essays on cinema and theater, debating such technical issues as segmentation, [[Cut-up technique|d√©coupage]], "photogenia" (founded on the [[Insert (filmmaking)|insert shot]]) and [[Film editing|rhythmic editing]].<ref name="dali collected writings">{{cite book|last=Dal√≠|first=Salvador|title=The Collected Writings of Salvador Dal√≠|year=1998|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-56027-6|url=http://www.paolocirio.net/work/amazon-noir/amazon-noir-books/AMAZON-NOIR--The_Collected_Writings_of_Salvador_Dal%C3%AD--By--Salvador_Dali_Haim_N_Finkelstein--0521560276.pdf}}</ref> He also collaborated with the celebrated writer [[Ram√≥n G√≥mez de la Serna]] on the script for what he hoped would be his first film, "a story in six scenes" called ''Los caprichos''.<ref name=talens />{{rp|pp.30‚Äì31}} Through his involvement with ''Gaceta Literaria'', he helped establish Madrid's first cine-club and served as its inaugural chairman.<ref name="gomez mesa">{{cite journal|last=G√≥mez Mesa|first=Luis.|title=La generaci√≥n cinematogr√°fica del '27|journal=Cinema 2002|year=1978|issue= 37|pages=52‚Äì58}}</ref>
It was during this time that he met his future wife, Jeanne Rucar Lefebvre,<ref>[[Lille]], 29 February 1908 [http://www.redaragon.com/trebede/feb2000/articulo2.asp] ‚Äì [[Mexico City]], 4 November 1994 [http://elpais.com/diario/1994/11/07/agenda/784162802_850215.html]</ref> a [[gymnastics]] teacher who had won an Olympic bronze medal. Bu√±uel courted her in a formal Aragonese manner, complete with a chaperone,<ref name="bbc world service">{{cite web|title=Luis Bu√±uel: In The Directors' Chair|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/arts/highlights/000919_bunuel.shtml|publisher=BBC World Service|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref> and they married in 1934<ref name="brain juice" /> despite a warning by Jean Epstein when Bu√±uel first proposed in 1930: "Jeanne, you are making a mistake... It's not right for you, don't marry him."<ref name="jeanne rucar">{{cite book|last=Rucar de Bu√±uel|first=Jeanne|title=Memoirs of a Woman Without a Piano: My Life with Luis Bu√±uel|year=2010|publisher=Five Ties Publishing|location=Brooklyn|isbn=978-0-9794727-6-3|pages=43}}</ref> The two remained married throughout his life and had two sons, [[Juan Luis Bu√±uel|Juan Luis]] and Rafael.<ref name="Centro Virtual Cervantes">{{cite web|title=Rafael Bunuel, Escultor|url=http://cvc.cervantes.es/actcult/bunuel/entrevistas/r_bunuel.htm|website=Centro Virtual Cervantes|publisher=Instituto Cervantes|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> [[Diego Bu√±uel]], filmmaker and host of the [[National Geographic Channel]]'s ''[[Don't Tell My Mother]]'' series, is their grandson.<ref name="nat geo">{{cite web|title=Nat Geo Adventure|url=http://natgeoadventure.tv/int/user.aspx?userid=10703|publisher=NGC-UK Partnership|accessdate=23 July 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813071957/http://natgeoadventure.tv/int/User.aspx?userId=10703|archivedate=13 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
====''Un Chien Andalou'' (1929)==== After this apprenticeship, Bu√±uel shot and directed a 16-minute short, ''[[Un Chien Andalou]]'', with [[Salvador Dal√≠]]. The film, financed by Bu√±uel's mother,<ref name="brain juice andalusian dog">{{cite web|title=Un chien Andalou (An Andalusian Dog, 1929) |url=http://www.brain-juice.com/cgi-bin/show_wok.cgi?p_id=136&w_id=391 |publisher=Brain-Juice.Com |accessdate=23 July 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061205212607/http://www.brain-juice.com/cgi-bin/show_wok.cgi?p_id=136&w_id=391 |archivedate=5 December 2006 |df= }}</ref> consists of a series of startling images of a [[Freudian]] nature,<ref name=mansfield>{{cite book|last=Mansfield|first=Nick|title=Subjectivity: Theories of the Self from Freud to Haraway|year=2000|publisher=New York University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8147-5650-8|pages=36|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qBVh5gVTlC4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> starting with a woman's eyeball being sliced open with a razor blade. ''Un Chien Andalou'' was enthusiastically received by the burgeoning French [[surrealism|surrealist]] movement of the time<ref name=richardson>{{cite book|last=Richardson|first=Michael|title=Surrealism and Cinema|year=2006|publisher=Berg|location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-84520-225-5|pages=27|url=https://books.google.com/?id=v1C6E_zJi6UC&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=chien+andalou+reception+surrealist#v=onepage&q=chien%20andalou%20reception%20surrealist}}</ref> and continues to be shown regularly in [[Film society|film societies]] to this day.<ref name=mathijs>{{cite book|last=Mathijs|first=Ernest|title=Cult Cinema|year=2011|publisher=Blackwell|location=West Sussex|isbn=978-1-4051-7374-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=uPtuaV7IAt0C&pg=PT194&lpg=PT194&dq=chien+andalou+film+societies#v=onepage&q=chien%20andalou%20film%20societies}}</ref>
The script was written in six days at Dal√≠'s home in [[Cadaqu√©s]]. In a letter to a friend written in February 1929, Bu√±uel described the writing process: "We had to look for the plot line. Dal√≠ said to me, 'I dreamed last night of ants swarming around in my hands', and I said, 'Good Lord, and I dreamed that I had sliced somebody or other's eye. There's the film, let's go and make it.'"<ref name=etherington-smith>{{cite book|last=Etherington-Smith|first=Meredith|title=The Persistence of Memory: A Biography of Dal√≠|year=1995|publisher=Da Capo Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-306-80662-9|pages=94|url=https://books.google.com/?id=soncxLrkYX0C&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=We+had+to+look+for+the+plot+line.+Dal%C3%AD+said+to+me,+%22I+dreamed+last+night+of+ants+swarming+around+in+my+hands%27,+and+I+said,+%22Good+Lord,+and+I+dreamed+that+I+had+sliced+somebody+or+other%27s+eye.+There%27s+the+film,+let%27s+go+and+make+it.#v=onepage&q=We%20had%20to%20look%20for%20the%20plot%20line.%20Dal%C3%AD%20said%20to%20me%2C%20%22I%20dreamed%20last%20night%20of%20ants%20swarming%20around%20in%20my%20hands%27%2C%20and%20I%20said%2C%20%22Good%20Lord%2C%20and%20I%20dreamed%20that%20I%20had%20sliced%20somebody%20or%20other%27s%20eye.%20There%27s%20the%20film%2C%20let%27s%20go%20and%20make%20it.}}</ref> In deliberate contrast to the approach taken by Jean Epstein and his peers, which was to never leave anything in their work to chance, with every aesthetic decision having a rational explanation and fitting clearly into the whole,<ref name="o'donoghue">{{cite web|last=O'Donoghue|first=Darragh|title=On Some Motifs in Poe: Jean Epstein's La Chute de la maison Usher|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2004/feature-articles/la_chute_de_la_maison_usher/#b4|publisher=Senses of Cinema|accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> Bu√±uel and Dal√≠ made a cardinal point of eliminating all logical associations.<ref name=Adamowicz>{{cite book|last=Adamowicz|first=Elza|title=Un Chien Andalou: (Luis Bu√±uel and Salvador Dal√≠, 1929)|year=2010|publisher=I.B.Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1-84885-056-9|pages=8|url=http://www.ibtauris.com/Books/The%20arts/Film%20TV%20%20radio/Films%20cinema/Film%20guides%20%20reviews/~/media/Files/Extracts/Visual%20Culture/9781848850569.ashx}}</ref> In Bu√±uel's words: "Our only rule was very simple: no idea or image that might lend itself to a rational explanation of any kind would be accepted. We had to open all doors to the irrational and keep only those images that surprised us, without trying to explain why".<ref name="my last sigh" />{{rp|p.104}} [[File:Andr√© Breton 1924.jpg|thumb|right|190px|Andr√© Breton 1924<br/>Breton defined Surrealism as: "Pure psychic automatism through which it is intended to express, either orally or in writing, or in any other way, the actual way thought works."<ref>{{cite book|last=Breton|first=Andre|title=Manifestoes of Surrealism|year=1969|publisher=University of Michigan Press|location=Ann Arbor|isbn=978-0-472-06182-2|page=3|title-link=Manifestoes of Surrealism}}</ref>]] It was Bu√±uel's intention to shock and insult the intellectual bourgeoisie of his youth, later saying: "Historically the film represents a violent reaction against what in those days was called 'avant-garde,' which was aimed exclusively at artistic sensibility and the audience's reason."<ref name="art in cinema">{{cite book|last=Bu√±uel|first=Luis|title="Notes on the Making of Un Chien Andalou", in Art in Cinema : documents toward a history of the film society|year=2006|publisher=Temple University Press|location=Philadelphia|isbn=978-1-59213-425-0|pages=101‚Äì102|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/32547313/Art-in-Cinema}}</ref> Against his hopes and expectations, the film was a huge success amongst the French bourgeoisie,<ref name=koller>{{cite web|last=Koller|first=Michael|title=Un Chien Andalou|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2001/cteq/chien/|website=Senses of Cinema|publisher=Film Victoria|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> leading Bu√±uel to exclaim in exasperation, "What can I do about the people who adore all that is new, even when it goes against their deepest convictions, or about the insincere, corrupt press, and the inane herd that saw beauty or poetry in something which was basically no more than a desperate impassioned call for murder?"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bu√±uel|first=Luis|title=Preface to the script for Un Chien Andalou|journal=La R√©volution Surr√©aliste|date=12 December 1929|volume=no. 12}}</ref>
Although ''Un Chien Andalou'' is a [[silent film]], during the original screening (attended by the elite of the Parisian art world), Bu√±uel played a sequence of phonograph records which he switched manually while keeping his pockets full of stones with which to pelt anticipated hecklers.<ref name="maverick arts">{{cite web|title=Un Chien Andalou|url=http://www.maverick-arts.com/cgi-bin/MAVERICK?&issue=340|publisher=Maverick Arts Magazine|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> After the premiere, Bu√±uel and Dal√≠ were granted formal admittance to the tight-knit community of Surrealists, led by poet [[Andr√© Breton]].<ref name=hoberman />
====''L'Age d'Or'' (1930)==== Late in 1929, on the strength of ''Un Chien Andalou'', Bu√±uel and Dal√≠ were commissioned to make another short film by [[Marie-Laure de Noailles|Marie-Laurie]] and [[Charles de Noailles]], owners of a private cinema on the [[Place des √âtats-Unis]] and financial supporters of productions by Jacques Manuel, [[Man Ray]] and [[Pierre Chenal]].<ref name="bfi vol 3" />{{rp|p.124}} At first, the intent was that the new film be around the same length as ''Un Chien'', only this time with sound. But by mid-1930, the film had grown segmentally to an hour's duration.<ref name="bfi vol 3" />{{rp|p.116}} Anxious that it was over twice as long as planned and at double the budget, Bu√±uel offered to trim the film and cease production, but Noailles gave him the go-ahead to continue the project.<ref name="bfi vol 3" />{{rp|p.116}}
The film, entitled ''[[L'Age d'Or]]'', was begun as a second collaboration with Dal√≠, but, while working on the scenario, the two had a falling out; Bu√±uel, who at the time had strong leftist sympathies,<ref name=gubern>{{cite book|last=Gubern|first=Rom√°n and Paul Hammond|title=Luis Bunuel: The Red Years, 1929‚Äì1939|year=2012|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison|isbn=978-0-299-28474-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=elueEkeLL_oC&pg=PA427&lpg=PA427&dq=bunuel+espana+1936#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20espana%201936}}</ref> desired a deliberate undermining of all bourgeois institutions, while Dal√≠, who eventually supported the Spanish nationalist dictator [[Francisco Franco]] and various figures of the European aristocracy, wanted merely to cause a scandal through the use of various [[Scatology|scatological]] and anti-Catholic images.<ref name="film reference">{{cite web|title=Marxism ‚Äì European Cinema Before and After World War II|url=http://www.filmreference.com/encyclopedia/Independent-Film-Road-Movies/Marxism-EUROPEAN-CINEMA-BEFORE-AND-AFTER-WORLD-WAR-II.html|website=film reference|publisher=Advameg, Inc.|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> The friction between them was exacerbated when, at a dinner party in Cadaqu√©s, Bu√±uel tried to throttle Dal√≠'s girlfriend, [[Gala Dal√≠|Gala]], the wife of Surrealist poet [[Paul √âluard]].<ref name=thurlow>{{cite book|last=Thurlow|first=Clifford|title=Making Short Films: The Complete Guide from Script to Screen, 2nd ed|year=2008|publisher=Berg|location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-84520-803-5|pages=3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HX8XcfTw6KIC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> In consequence, Dal√≠ had nothing to do with the actual shooting of the film.<ref name=dali>{{cite book|last=Dal√≠|first=Salvador|title=The Secret Life of Salvador Dali|year=1942|publisher=Dial Press|location=New York}}</ref>{{rp|pp.276‚Äì277}} During the course of production, Bu√±uel worked around his technical ignorance by filming mostly in sequence and using nearly every foot of film that he shot. Bu√±uel invited friends and acquaintances to appear, gratis, in the film; for example, anyone who owned a tuxedo or a party frock got a part in the salon scene.<ref name="bfi vol 3" />{{rp|p.116}}
{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=left|width=25%|quote="A film called ''L'Age d'or'', whose non-existent artistic quality is an insult to any kind of technical standard, combines, as a public spectacle, the most obscene, disgusting and tasteless incidents. Country, family, and religion are dragged through the mud".<ref>{{cite news|last=Bodin|first=Richard Pierre|title=Review of "L'age d'Or"|newspaper=Le Figaro|date=7 December 1930}}</ref> |source=Excerpt from Richard Pierre Bodin's review in ''[[Le Figaro]]'', 7 December 1930.}} ''L'Age d'Or'' was publicly proclaimed by Dal√≠ as a deliberate attack on Catholicism, and this precipitated a much larger scandal than ''Un Chien Andalou''.<ref name=fanes>{{cite book|last=Fan√©s|first=F√®lix|title=Salvador Dali: The Construction of the Image|year=2007|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven|isbn=978-0-300-09179-3|pages=171|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bDpziok_K7gC&pg=PA171&lpg=PA171&dq=l%27age+d%27or+dali+dispute+bunuel#v=onepage&q=l%27age%20d%27or%20dali%20dispute%20bunuel}}</ref> One early screening was taken over by members of the fascist [[Ligue des Patriotes|League of Patriots]] and the Anti-Jewish Youth Group, who hurled purple ink at the screen<ref name="ado kyrou">{{cite book|last=Kyrou|first=Ado|title=Luis Bu√±uel: an introduction|year=1963|publisher=Simon and Schuster|location=New York|pages=30}}</ref> and then vandalised the adjacent art gallery, destroying a number of valuable surrealist paintings.<ref name=moria>{{cite web|last=Scheib|first=Richard|title=L'Age d'Or|url=http://www.moria.co.nz/fantasy/lagedor.htm|publisher=Moria ‚Äì The Science Fiction, Horror and Fantasy Film Review|accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref> The film was banned by the Parisian police "in the name of public order".<ref name="Instituto Cervantes">{{cite book|last=Instituto Cervantes|title=Bu√±uel, 100 a√±o: es peligroso asomarse al Interior/ Bu√±uel, 100 Years: It' s Dangerous to Look Inside|year=2001|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8109-6219-4|pages=62}}</ref> The de Noailles, both Catholics, were threatened with [[Excommunication#Roman Catholic Church|excommunication]] by [[Holy See|The Vatican]] because of the film's blasphemous final scene (which visually links [[Jesus Christ]] with the writings of the [[Marquis de Sade]]), so they made the decision in 1934 to withdraw all prints from circulation, and ''L'Age d'Or'' was not seen again until 1979, after their deaths,<ref name=laufer>{{cite web|last=Laufer|first=Laura|title=L'√Çge d'or" de Luis Bunuel|url=http://adagio.over-blog.fr/article-25951854.html|publisher=Le Centre Georges-Pompidou|accessdate=23 July 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615233326/http://adagio.over-blog.fr/article-25951854.html|archivedate=15 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> although a print was smuggled to England for private viewing.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lim|first1=Dennis|title=The Village Voice Film Guide: 50 Years of Movies from Classics to Cult Hits|date=2006|publisher=Wiley|location=New York|isbn=978-0471787815|page=7|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yHcIp0sa6MkC&pg=PA7&dq=l%27age+d%27or+banned#v=onepage&q=l'age%20d'or%20banned|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> The furor was so great that the premiere of another film financed by the de Noailles, [[Jean Cocteau]]'s ''[[The Blood of a Poet]]'', had to be delayed for over two years until outrage over ''L'Age d'Or'' had died down.<ref name=burke>{{cite book|last=Burke|first=Carolyn|title=Lee Miller: A Life|year=2005|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-375-40147-3|pages=114|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PVmJOWev0p8C&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113&dq=Noailles+excommunication#v=onepage&q=Noailles%20excommunication}}</ref> To make matters worse, Charles de Noailles was forced to withdraw his membership from the [[Jockey-Club de Paris|Jockey Club]].<ref name=teitelbaum>{{cite book|last=Teitelbaum|first=Mo Amelia|title=The Stylemakers: Minimalism and Classic-Modernism 1915‚Äì45|year=2010|publisher=Philip Willson|location=London|isbn=978-0-85667-703-8|pages=102|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CuT3JqcH8hcC&pg=PA102&lpg=PA102&dq=charles+de+noailles+jockey+club#v=onepage&q=charles%20de%20noailles%20jockey%20club}}</ref>
Concurrent with the ''[[succ√®s de scandale]]'', both Bu√±uel and the film's leading lady, [[Lya Lys]], received offers of interest from [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] and traveled to Hollywood at the studio's expense.<ref name=durgnat>{{cite book|last=Durgnat|first=Raymond|title=Luis Bu√±uel|year=1968|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley}}</ref> While in the United States, Bu√±uel associated with other celebrity expatriates including [[Sergei Eisenstein]], [[Josef Von Sternberg]], Jacques Feyder, [[Charles Chaplin]] and [[Bertolt Brecht]].<ref name="brain juice" /> All that was required of Bu√±uel by his loose-ended contract with MGM was that he "learn some good American technical skills",<ref name=walters>{{cite book|last=Walters|first=Rob|title=Spread Spectrum: Hedy Lamarr And the Mobile Phone|year=2006|publisher=BookSurge Publishing|location=Great Britain|isbn=978-1-4196-2129-1|pages=65|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ciuJ0UTCnmQC&pg=PA65&lpg=PA65&dq=luis+bunuel+MGM#v=onepage&q=luis%20bunuel%20MGM}}</ref> but, after being ushered off the first set he visited because the star, [[Greta Garbo]], did not welcome intruders, he decided to stay at home most of the time and only show up to collect his paycheck.<ref name=Doniol-Valcroze>{{cite journal|last=Doniol-Valcroze|first=Jacques|author2=Andr√© Bazin|title=Entretien avec Luis Bu√±uel|journal=Cahiers du Cinema|date=July 1954|issue=37|pages=44‚Äì48}}</ref> His only enduring contribution to MGM came when he served as an extra in ''La Fruta Amarga'', a Spanish-language remake of ''[[Min and Bill]]''.<ref name=jarvinen>{{cite book|last=Jarvinen|first=Lisa|title=The Rise of Spanish-Language Filmmaking: Out from Hollywood's Shadow, 1929‚Äì1939|year=2012|publisher=Rutgers University Press|location=Piscataway NJ|isbn=978-0-8135-5328-3|pages=58|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W10o8udrUakC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> When, after a few months at the studio, he was asked to watch [[Dailies|rushes]] of [[Lili Damita]] to gauge her Spanish accent, he refused and sent a message to studio boss [[Irving Thalberg]] stating that he was there as a Frenchman, not a Spaniard, and he "didn't have time to waste listening to one of the whores".<ref name=bazin>{{cite book|last=Bazin|first=Andre|title=Bu≈Üuel, Dreyer, Welles|year=1991|publisher=Editorial Fundamentos|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-245-0521-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=S4mCa7JzhI8C&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=luis+bunuel+damita#v=onepage&q=luis%20bunuel%20damita}}</ref>{{rp|p.18}} He was back in Spain shortly thereafter.<ref name=durgnat />
===Spain (1931‚Äì1937)=== <!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Screen capture of classroom scene from Las Hurdas, Tierra Sin Pan.jpeg|299px|thumb|The classroom scene from ''Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan'' is an ironic statement of Bu√±uel's Marxist sympathies.<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.59}}]] --> Spain in the early 1930s was a time of political and social turbulence, a period of intense and bloody upheaval.<ref name=blinkhorn>{{cite book|last=Blinkhorn|first=Martin|title=Democracy And Civil War in Spain 1931‚Äì1939|year=1988|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=978-0-415-00699-6|pages=3‚Äì31|url=https://books.google.com/?id=CnJawWYdjNUC&printsec=frontcover&dq=spain+1931+upheaval#v=onepage&q=spain%201931%20upheaval}}</ref> Anarchists and [[Radical Socialist Republican Party|Radical Socialists]] sacked [[Monarchism|monarchist]] headquarters in [[Madrid]] and proceeded to set afire or otherwise wreck more than a dozen churches in the capital while similar revolutionary acts occurred in a score of other cities in southern and eastern Spain, in most cases with the acquiescence and occasionally with the assistance of the official Republican authorities.<ref name=payne>{{cite book|last=Payne|first=Stanley G.|title=A History of Spain and Portugal, V. 2|year=1976|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison|isbn=978-0-299-06284-2|pages=630|url=http://libro.uca.edu/payne2/payne25.htm}}</ref>
Bu√±uel's future wife, Jeanne Rucar, recalled that during that period, "he got very excited about politics and the ideas that were everywhere in pre-Civil War Spain".<ref name="rucar de bunuel espanol">{{cite book|last=Rucar de Bu√±uel|first=Jeanne|title=Memorias de un mujer sin piano|year=1990|publisher=Alianza Editorial|location=Madrid|isbn=978-9683903907|pages=58}}</ref> In the first flush of his enthusiasm, Bu√±uel joined the [[Communist Party of Spain]] (PCE) in 1931<ref name=gubern />{{rp|pp.85‚Äì114}} though later in life he denied becoming a Communist.<ref name=aub>{{cite book|last=Aub|first=Max|title=Conversaciones con Bu√±uel: Seguidas de 45 entrevistas con familiares, amigos y colaboradores del cineasta aragon√©s |year=1985|publisher=Aguilar|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-03-09195-5}}</ref>{{rp|p.72}}
[[File:Screen capture from Las Hurdas, Tierra Sin Pan.jpeg|left|thumb|269px|An early scene from ''Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan'' depicts a local wedding custom where the bridegroom tears the head off a rooster suspended by its feet from a scaffold above the main street of town.<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.57}}]] In 1932, Bu√±uel was invited to serve as film documentarian for the celebrated ''Mission Dakar-Djibouti'', the first large-scale French anthropological field expedition, which, led by [[Marcel Griaule]], unearthed some 3,500 African artifacts for the new [[Mus√©e de l'Homme]].<ref name=ruoff-45>{{cite journal|last=Ruoff|first=Jeffrey|title=An Ethnographic Surrealist Film: Luis Bu√±uel's Land Without Bread|url=https://www.dartmouth.edu/~jruoff/Articles/EthnographicSurrealist.htm|journal=Visual Anthropology Review|date=Spring‚ÄìSummer 1998|volume=14|issue=1|pages=45‚Äì57|accessdate=10 January 2016|doi=10.1525/var.1998.14.1.45}}</ref> Although he declined, the project piqued his interest in [[ethnography]]. After reading the academic study, ''Las Jurdes: √©tude de g√©ographie humaine'' (1927) by Maurice Legendre, he decided to make a film focused on [[peasant]] life in [[Extremadura]], one of Spain's poorest states.<ref name=margulies>{{cite book|last=Margulies|first=Ivone|title=Rites of Realism: Essays on Corporeal Cinema|year=2003|publisher=Duke University Press|location=Durham, NC|isbn=978-0-8223-3078-3|pages=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UP3Gf8KfsXwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> The film, called ''[[Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan]]'' (1933), was financed on a budget of 20,000 pesetas donated by a working-class [[anarchist]] friend named [[Ram√≥n Ac√≠n]], who had won the money in a lottery.<ref name=weir>{{cite book|last=Weir|first=David|title=Anarchy & Culture: The Aesthetic Politics of Modernism|year=1997|publisher=University of Massachusetts Press|location=Amherst| isbn=978-1-55849-083-3| pages=253 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=fRR8eWzRhbYC&pg=PA253&lpg=PA253&dq=las+hurdes+acin#v=onepage&q=las%20hurdes%20acin}}</ref> In the film, Bu√±uel matches scenes of deplorable social conditions with narration that resembles travelogue commentary delivered by a detached-sounding announcer,<ref name="Harvard Film Archive">{{cite web|title=Bu√±uel: The Beginning and the End|url=http://hcl.harvard.edu/hfa/films/2011aprjun/bunuel.html|publisher=Harvard Film Archive|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> while the soundtrack thunders inappropriate music by [[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]].
{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote="Though the material is organized with masterly skill, the very conception of 'art' here seems irrelevant. It is the most profoundly disturbing film I have ever seen."<ref name="tony richardson">{{cite book|last=Richardson|first=Tony|title="The Films of Luis Bu√±uel," in The World of Luis Bu√±uel, ed. Joan Mellen|year=1978|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-19-502398-5|pages=129}}</ref> |source=Award-winning film director [[Tony Richardson]] on ''Las Hurdes: Tierra Sin Pan''}}
''Las Hurdes'' was banned by three successive Republican governments, definitively by [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] when he came to power.<ref name=Russell>{{cite web|last=Russell|first=Dominique|title=Luis Bu√±uel|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2005/great-directors/bunuel/|website=Great Directors, Issue 35|publisher=Senses of Cinema|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> It is a film which continues to perplex viewers and resists easy categorization by film historians.<ref name=juhasz>{{cite book|last=Juhasz |first=Alexandra|title=F Is For Phony: Fake Documentary And Truth's Undoing|year=2006|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4251-9|pages=101|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TXaFokB-qx4C&dq=bunuel+las+hurdes+reading+ethnographic}}</ref> ''Las Hurdes'' has been called one of the first examples of [[mockumentary]],<ref name=mockumentary>{{cite web|title=Week 16: Mockumentary|url=http://www.documentarysite.com/?p=101|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130121172356/http://www.documentarysite.com/?p=101|dead-url=yes|archive-date=21 January 2013|website=Documentary film and video course syllabus.|publisher=Documentary Site|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> and has been labeled a "surrealist documentary", a term defined by critic Merc√® Ibarz as "A multi-layered and unnerving use of sound, the juxtaposition of narrative forms already learnt from the written press, travelogues and new pedagogic methods, as well as a subversive use of photographed and filmed documents understood as a basis for contemporary propaganda for the masses".<ref name=ibarz>{{cite book|last=Ibarz|first=Merc√®|title="A Serious Experiment: Land Without Bread, 1933", in Luis Bu√±uel: New Readings. ed. Isabel Santaolalla and Peter William Evans|year=2004|publisher=British Film Institute |location=London| isbn=978-1-84457-003-4|pages=28}}</ref> Catherine Russell has stated that in ''Las Hurdes'', Bu√±uel was able to reconcile his political philosophy with his surrealist aesthetic, with surrealism becoming "a means of awakening a marxist materialism in danger of becoming a stale orthodoxy."<ref>{{cite book|last=Russell|first=Catherine|title="Surrealist Ethnography: Las Hurdes and the Documentary Unconscious", in F Is for Phony: Fake Documentary And Truth's Undoing, edited by Alexandra Juhasz and Jesse Lerner|year=2006|publisher=U of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4251-9|page=112|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TXaFokB-qx4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>
After ''Las Hurdes'' in 1933, Bu√±uel worked in Paris in the [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbing]] department of [[Paramount Pictures]], but following his marriage in 1934, he switched to [[Warner Brothers]] because they operated dubbing studios in Madrid.<ref name=acevedo-munoz>{{cite book|last=Acevedo-Mu√±oz|first=Ernesto R.|title=Bu√±uel and Mexico: The Crisis of National Cinema|year=2003|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles| isbn=978-0-520-23952-4| url=https://books.google.com/?id=M-Q1iOxo00wC&dq=bunuel+filmofono}}</ref>{{rp|p.39}} A friend, Ricardo Urgoiti, who owned the commercial film company Film√≥fono, invited Bu√±uel to [[Film producer|produce]] films for a mass audience. He accepted the offer, viewing it as an "experiment" as he knew the film industry in Spain was still far behind the technical level of Hollywood or Paris.<ref name=higginbotham>{{cite book|last=Higginbotham|first=Virginia|title=Luis Bu√±uel|year=1979|publisher=Twayne Publishers|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8057-9261-4}}</ref>{{rp|p.56}} According to film historian Manuel Rotellar's interviews with members of the cast and crew of the Film√≥fono studios, Bu√±uel's only condition was that his involvement with these pictures be completely anonymous, apparently for fear of damaging his reputation as a surrealist.<ref name=rotellar>{{cite journal|last=Rotellar|first=Manuel|title=Luis Bu√±uel en Film√≥fono|journal=Cinema 2002|year=1978|issue= 37|pages=36‚Äì40}}</ref> Rotellar insists, however, "the truth is that it was Luis Bu√±uel who directed the Film√≥fono productions".<ref name=rotellar />{{rp|p.37}} [[Jos√© Luis S√°enz de Heredia]], the titular director of two of the films created during Bu√±uel's years as "executive producer" at Film√≥fono, recounted that it was Bu√±uel who "explained to me every morning what he wanted...We looked at the takes together and it was Bu√±uel who chose the shots, and in editing, I wasn't even allowed to be present."<ref name=rotellar />{{rp|p.39}} Of the 18 films produced by Bu√±uel during his years at Film√≥fono, the four that are believed by critical consensus to have been directed by him<ref name=mortimore>{{cite journal|last=Mortimore|first=Roger|title=Bu√±uel, S√°enz de Heredia, and Film√≥fono|journal=Sight and Sound|date=Summer 1975|volume=44|pages=180‚Äì182}}</ref> are: <blockquote> * ''Don Quint√≠n el amargao'' (Don Quintin the Sourpuss), 1935 ‚Äì a musical based on a play by [[Carlos Arniches]],<ref name="fuentes, victor">{{cite book|last=Fuentes|first=Victor|title=Los mundos de Bu√±uel|year=2000|publisher=[[Ediciones Akal]]|location=Madrid|isbn=978-84-460-1450-8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Mdz1N3xs24IC&pg=PA57&lpg=PA57&dq=Don+Quint%C3%ADn+el+amargao+arniches+bunuel#v=onepage&q=Don%20Quint%C3%ADn%20el%20amargao%20arniches%20bunuel}}</ref> the first ''[[zarzuela]]'' (a type of Spanish opera) filmed in sound.<ref>{{cite web|title=Don Quint√≠n el Amargao on AllMovie Don Quint√≠n el Amargao (1935)|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/don-quint%C3%ADn-el-amargao-v235543|website=allmovie.com|publisher=AllMovie, a division of All Media Network|accessdate=2 November 2013}}</ref> * ''[[La hija de Juan Sim√≥n]]'' (Juan Sim√≥n's Daughter), 1935 ‚Äì another musical and a major commercial success<ref name=bentley>{{cite book|last=Bentley|first=Bernard P. E.|title=A Companion to Spanish Cinema|year=2008|publisher=Tamesis|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk|isbn=978-1-85566-176-9|pages=61|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M6kRqqwNMm0C&pg=PA61#v=onepage}}</ref> * ''¬øQui√©n me quiere a m√≠?'' (Who Loves Me?), 1936 ‚Äì a sentimental comedy that Bu√±uel called "my only commercial failure, and a pretty dismal one at that."<ref name="my last sigh" />{{rp|p.144}} * ''¬°Centinela, alerta!'', (Sentry, Keep Watch!), 1937 ‚Äì a comedy and Film√≥fono's biggest box-office hit.<ref name=bentley /> </blockquote>
During the [[Spanish Civil War]] (1936‚Äì1939), Bu√±uel placed himself at the disposal of the Republican government.<ref name="an unspeakable betrayal">{{cite book|last=Bu√±uel|first=Luis|title=An Unspeakable Betrayal: Selected Writings of Luis Bu√±uel|year=2002|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles|isbn=978-0-520-23423-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tK3KPgv34U8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.255}} The minister for foreign affairs sent him first to [[Geneva]] {{when|date=January 2016}} and then to Paris{{when|date=January 2016}} for two years, with official responsibility for cataloging Republican propaganda films.<ref name=edwards />{{rp|p.6}} Besides the cataloguing, Bu√±uel took left-wing tracts to Spain, did some occasional spying, acted as a bodyguard, and supervised the making of a documentary, entitled ''[[Espa√±a 1936 (film)|Espa√±a 1936]]'' in France and ''Espana leal, ¬°en armas!'' in Spain, that covered the elections, the parades, the riots, and the war.<ref name="del olmo">{{cite journal|last=del Olmo|first=F. Javier Ruiz|title=Language and Collective Identity in Bu√±uel. Propaganda in the Film "Espa√±a 1936" |journal=Comunicar| year=2010|volume=XVIII|issue=35|pages=69‚Äì76|doi=10.3916/C35-2010-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Espana leal, en armas|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b712e8a58|website=BFI Film Forever|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=6 August 2012}}</ref> In August 1936, [[Federico Garc√≠a Lorca]] was shot and killed by Nationalist militia.<ref name=beevor>{{cite book|last=Beevor|first=Antony|title=The Battle for Spain. The Spanish Civil War 1936‚Äì1939|year=2006|publisher=Penguin Books|location=London|isbn=978-0-14-303765-1|pages=100}}</ref> According to his son, [[Juan Luis Bu√±uel|Juan Luis]], Bu√±uel rarely talked about Lorca but mourned the poet's untimely death throughout his life.<ref name=ehrlich>{{cite web|last=Ehrlich|first=Linda C.|title=A Bu√±uel Scrapbook: The Last Script: Remembering Luis Bu√±uel (1) and Calanda: 40 Years Later| url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2009/feature-articles/last-script-bunuel-calanda/|publisher=Senses of Cinema|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref>
Bu√±uel essentially functioned as the coordinator of film propaganda for the Republic, which meant that he was in a position to examine all film shot in the country and decide what sequences could be developed and distributed abroad.<ref name=faber>{{cite web|last=Faber|first=Sebastiaan|title=Luis Bu√±uel, chameleon: Revelations from the "Red Decade" |url=http://www.albavolunteer.org/2011/12/luis-bunuel-chameleon-revelations-from-the-%E2%80%9Cred-decade%E2%80%9D/|website=The Volunteer|publisher=Abraham Lincoln Brigade Archives (ALBA)|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> The Spanish Ambassador suggested that Bu√±uel revisit Hollywood where he could give technical advice on films being made there about the Spanish Civil War,<ref name=edwards />{{rp|p.6}} so in 1938, he and his family traveled to the United States using funds obtained from his old patrons, the Noailles.<ref name=hoberman>{{cite journal|last=Hoberman|first=J.|title=A Charismatic Chameleon: On Luis Bu√±uel|journal=The Nation|date=14 May 2012|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/167559/charismatic-chameleon-luis-bunuel#|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> Almost immediately upon his arrival in America, however, the war ended and the [[Motion Picture Association of America|Motion Picture Producers and Distributors Association of America]] discontinued making films on the Spanish conflict.<ref name="robert cole">{{cite book|last=Cole|first=Robert|title=Propaganda, Censorship And Irish Neutrality in the Second World War|year=2006|publisher=Edinburgh University Press |location=Edinburgh| isbn=978-0-7486-2277-1|pages=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wu_bOQiXGs4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> According to Bu√±uel's wife, returning to Spain was impossible since the 'Fascists' had seized power,<ref name="rucar de bunuel espanol" />{{rp|p.63‚Äì64}} so Bu√±uel decided to stay in the U.S. indefinitely, stating that he was "immensely attracted by the American naturalness and sociability."<ref name="an unspeakable betrayal" />{{rp|p.255}}
===United States (1938‚Äì1945)=== [[File:Museum of modern art airways to peace exhibition 1943.jpg|295px|thumb|Museum of Modern Art, 1943]] Returning to Hollywood in 1938, he was befriended by Frank Davis, an MGM producer and member of the [[Communist Party USA]],<ref name=gubern />{{rp|p.349}} who placed Bu√±uel on the payroll of ''Cargo of Innocence'', a film about Spanish refugee mothers and children fleeing from [[Bilbao]] to the USSR.<ref name="edwards - lorca etc.">{{cite book|last=Edwards|first=Gwynne|title=Lorca, Bu√±uel, Dal√≠: forbidden pleasures and connected lives|year=2009|publisher=I. B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1-84885-007-1|pages=194}}</ref> The project was shelved precipitately when another Hollywood film about the Spanish Civil War, ''[[Blockade (1938 film)|Blockade]]'', was met with disfavor by the [[National Legion of Decency|Catholic League of Decency]].<ref name=manchel>{{cite book|last=Manchel|first=Frank|title=Film Study: An Analytical Bibliography, Volume 1|year=1990|publisher=Associated University Presses|location=Cranbury NJ|isbn=978-0-8386-3186-7|pages=219‚Äì220}}</ref> In the words of biographer Ruth Brandon, Bu√±uel and his family "lived from one unsatisfactory crumb of work to another" because he "had none of the arrogance and pushiness essential for survival in Hollywood."<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.358}} He just wasn't flamboyant enough to capture the attention of Hollywood decision makers, in the opinion of film composer [[George Antheil]]: "Inasmuch as [Bu√±uel], his wife and his little boy seemed to be such absolutely normal, solid persons, as totally un-Surrealist in the Dal√≠ tradition as one could possibly imagine."<ref name=baxter>{{cite book|last=Baxter|first=John|title=Bu√±uel|year=1994|publisher=Carroll & Graf|location=New York|isbn=978-0-7867-0619-8}}</ref>{{rp|p.172}} For the most part, he was snubbed by many of the people in the film community whom he met during his first trip to America,<ref>{{cite news|title=A documentary shows the most bitter of Bu√±uel and intimate portrait|url=http://www.deltaworld.org/cinema/A-documentary-shows-the-most-bitter-of-Bu-uel-and-intimate-portrait/|accessdate=8 August 2012|newspaper=The Delta World.|date=13 July 2012}}</ref> although he was able to sell some gags to Chaplin for his film ''[[The Great Dictator]]''.<ref name=taylor />{{rp|p.213}}
In desperation, to market himself to independent producers, he composed a 21-page autobiography, a section of which, headed "My Present Plans", outlined proposals for two documentary films: * "The Primitive Man", which would depict "the terrible struggle of primitive man against a hostile universe, how the world appeared, ''how they saw it'', what ideas they had on love, on death, on fraternity, how and why religion is born", [italics in original] * "Psycho-Pathology", which would "expose the origin and development of different psychopathic diseases... Such a documental film, apart from its great scientific interest, could depict on screen a ''New Form of Terror'' or its synonym ''Humour''." [italics in original]<ref name="an unspeakable betrayal" />{{rp|p.257}}
Nobody showed any interest and Bu√±uel realized that staying in Los Angeles was futile, so he traveled to New York to see if he could change his fortunes.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.174}}
{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=left|width=25%|quote="Luis Bu√±uel was there, with his thyroid eyes, the moles on his chin which I remember from so long ago when we first saw the surrealist films in the [[Cin√©math√®que Fran√ßaise|Cin√©math√®que]],... and as he talked I remember thinking that his paleness was most appropriate for someone who spent his life in dark projection rooms... He has a sharp humor, a bitter sarcasm, and at the same time towards women a gentle, special smile".<ref name=Nin>{{cite book|last=Nin|first=Anais|title=Diary of Ana√Øs Nin Volume 3 1939‚Äì1944: Vol. 3 (1939‚Äì1944)|year=1969|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|location=New York|isbn=978-0-15-626027-5|pages=109|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=igytZ9t8jsAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> |source=[[Ana√Øs Nin]], in her diary entry on encountering Bu√±uel when he was working at MoMA}} In New York, Antheil introduced Bu√±uel to [[Iris Barry]], chief curator of film at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA).<ref name=brandon />{{rp|p.360}} Barry talked Bu√±uel into joining a committee formed to help educate those within the U.S. government who might not have appreciated fully the effectiveness of film as a medium of propaganda. Bu√±uel was hired to produce a shortened version of [[Leni Riefenstahl]]'s ''[[Triumph of the Will]]'' (1935) as a demonstration project.<ref name=trimborn>{{cite book|last=Trimborn|first=J√ºrgen|title=Leni Riefenstahl: A Life|year=2007|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|location=New York|isbn=978-0-374-18493-3|pages=123‚Äì124|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4IFvjEArNg8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> The finished product was a compilation of scenes from Riefenstahl's [[Nazism|Nazi]] epic with [[Hans Bertram]]'s ''Feuertaufe''.<ref name=higginbotham />{{rp|p.58}} Bu√±uel stayed at MoMA to work for the [[Office of the Coordinator of Inter-American Affairs]] (OCIAA) as part of a production team that would gather, review and edit films intended as anti-fascist propaganda to be distributed in [[Latin America]] by American embassies.<ref name=schreiber>{{cite book|last=Schreiber|first=Rebecca M.|title=Cold War Exiles in Mexico: U.S. Dissidents and the Culture of Critical Resistance|year=2008|publisher=Univ of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4308-0|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4O1AElNqAZYC&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72&dq=bunuel+museum+of+modern+art#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20museum%20of%20modern%20art}}</ref>{{rp|p.72}} While being vetted for the job at the OCIAA, upon being asked if he was a Communist, he replied: "I am a Republican," and, apparently, the interviewer did not realize that Bu√±uel was referring to the Spanish socialist coalition government, not the American political party.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.180}} Describing Bu√±uel's work at MoMA, his friend, composer Gustavo Pittaluga, stated: "Luis created maybe 2,000 remarkable works. We were sent anodyne documentaries, often extremely feeble primary materials, which the Museum team turned into marvellous films. And not just Spanish versions, but also Portuguese, French and English... He would ''create'' a good documentary through editing." [italics in original]<ref name=aranda>{{cite book|last=Aranda|first=Francisco|title=Luis Bu√±uel: A Critical Biography|year=1976|publisher=Da Capo Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-306-70754-4}}</ref>{{rp|p.124}}
In 1942, Bu√±uel applied for American citizenship, because he anticipated that MoMA would soon be put under federal control.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.183}} But that same year, Dal√≠ published his autobiography, ''[[The Secret Life of Salvador Dal√≠]]'', in which he made it clear that he had split with Bu√±uel because the latter was a Communist and an [[atheist]].<ref name=navarro>{{cite book|last=Navarro|first=Vicente|title="The Jackboot of Dada", in Serpents in the Garden: Liaisons with Culture & Sex, ed. Alexander Cockburn and Jeffery St. Clair|year=2004|publisher=AK Press|location=Oakland, CA|isbn=978-1-902593-94-4|pages=148‚Äì149|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ShbksjUcH5YC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> News of this reached [[Francis Spellman|Archbishop Spellman]], who angrily confronted Barry with the question: "Are you aware that you are harbouring in this Museum the Antichrist, the man who made a blasphemous film ''L'Age d'Or''?"<ref name=taylor>{{cite book|last=Taylor|first=John Russell|title=Strangers in paradise: the Hollywood √©migr√©s, 1933‚Äì1950|year=1983|publisher=Holt, Rinehart & Winston|location=New York|isbn=978-0-03-061944-1}}</ref>{{rp|p.214}} At the same time, a campaign on the part of Hollywood, through its industry trade paper, the ''[[Motion Picture Herald]]'', to undermine the MoMA film unit resulted in a 66% reduction in the department's budget and Bu√±uel felt himself compelled to resign.<ref name="robert sitton">{{cite book|last1=Sitton|first1=Robert|title=Lady in the Dark: Iris Barry and the Art of Film|date=2014|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0231165785|page=317|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fyMZBQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=16 January 2015}}</ref> In 1944, he returned to Hollywood for the third time, this time as Spanish Dubbing Producer for [[Warner Brothers]].<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.190}} Before leaving New York, he confronted Dal√≠ at his hotel, the [[Sherry Netherland Hotel|Sherry Netherland]], to tell the painter about the damage his book had done and then shoot him in the knee.<ref name="don harrison">{{cite web|last=Harrison|first=Don|title=15 Footnotes on the Moustache of Bunuel ‚Äì Episodes of Luis|url=http://www.naderlibrary.com/bunuel15footnotesmoustache.htm|publisher=American Buddha|accessdate=21 August 2012}}</ref> Bu√±uel did not carry out the violent part of his plan. Dal√≠ explained himself by saying: "I did not write my book to put YOU on a pedestal. I wrote it to put ME on a pedestal".<ref name="don harrison" />
[[File:Man Ray 1934.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Man Ray ‚Äì a friend from Bu√±uel's surrealist period and collaborator on unrealized Hollywood projects]] Bu√±uel's first dubbing assignment on returning to Hollywood was ''[[My Reputation]]'', a [[Barbara Stanwyck]] picture which became ''El Que Diran'' in Bu√±uel's hands.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.190}} In addition to his dubbing work, Bu√±uel attempted to develop a number of independent projects: * In collaboration with an old friend from his Surrealist days, [[Man Ray]], he worked on a scenario called ''The Sewers of Los Angeles'', which took place on a mountain of excrement close to a highway and a dust basin.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.129}} * With his friend, [[Jos√© Rubia Barcia]], he co-wrote a screenplay called ''La novia de medianoche'' (The Midnight Bride), a gothic thriller, which lay dormant until it was filmed by Antonio Sim√≥n in 1997.<ref>{{cite book|last=Barcia|first=Jos√© Rubia|title=Con Luis Bu√±uel en Hollywood y despu√©s|year=1992|publisher=Edici√≥s do Castro|location=Sada, A Coru√±a|isbn=978-84-7492-582-1|pages=105‚Äì160}}</ref> * He continued working on a screenplay called "Goya and the Duchess of Alba", a treatment he had started as early as 1927, with the actor/producer [[Flori√°n Rey]] and cameraman [[Jos√© Mar√≠a Beltr√°n]], and then resuscitated in 1937 as a project for Paramount.<ref>{{cite book|last=S√°nchez Vidal|first=Agust√≠n|title=G√≥ngora, Bu√±uel, Spanish Avant-Garde and Centenary of Goya's Death, in The Spanish Avant-Garde, ed. Derek Harris|year=1995|publisher=Manchester University Press|location=Manchester|isbn=978-0-7190-4342-0|pages=117|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cQbpAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> * In his 1982 autobiography ''Mon Dernier soupir'' (''My Last Sigh'', 1983, ''My Last Breath'', 1994), Bu√±uel wrote that at the request of director [[Robert Florey]], he submitted a treatment of a scene about a disembodied hand, which was later included in the movie ''[[The Beast with Five Fingers]]'' (1946), starring [[Peter Lorre]], without acknowledgement of Bu√±uel's contribution or payment of any compensation.<ref name="my last sigh" />{{rp|p.189}} However, Brian Taves, film scholar and archivist with the [[Library of Congress]], has challenged the truth of this claim.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Taves|first=Brian|title=Whose Hand? Correcting a Bu√±uel myth|journal=Sight and Sound|date=Summer 1987|volume=56|issue=3|pages=210‚Äì211}}</ref>
In 1945, Bu√±uel's contract with Warner Brothers expired, and he decided not to renew it in order, as he put it: "to realize my life's ambition for a year: to do nothing".<ref name="bazin cinema of cruelty">{{cite book|last=Bazin|first=Andr√©|title=The cinema of cruelty: from Bu√±uel to Hitchcock|year=1982|publisher=Seaver Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0-86579-018-6|pages=89}}</ref> While his family enjoyed themselves at the beach, Bu√±uel spent much of his time in [[Antelope Valley]] with new acquaintances writer [[Aldous Huxley]] and sculptor [[Alexander Calder]], from whom he rented a house.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.130}}
In his autobiography, in a chapter about his second spell in America, Bu√±uel states that "[o]n several occasions, both American and European producers have suggested that I tackle a film version of [[Malcolm Lowry]]'s ''[[Under the Volcano]]''".<ref name="my last sigh" />{{rp|p.194}} He says that he read the book many times as well as eight different screenplays but was unable to come up with a solution for the cinema. [[Under the Volcano (film)|The movie]] was eventually made in 1984 by [[John Huston]].
===Intermediate years (1946‚Äì1961)===
====Mexico (1946‚Äì1953)====
The following year, an old friend, producer [[Denise Batcheff|Denise Tual]], the widow of [[Pierre Batcheff]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Pallister|first=Janis L.|title=French-Speaking Women Film Directors: A Guide|year=1997|publisher=Fairleigh Dickinson Univ Press|location=Madison NJ|isbn=978-0-8386-3736-4|pages=93}}</ref> the [[leading man]] in ''Un Chien Andalou'', proposed that she and Bu√±uel adapt Lorca's play ''[[The House of Bernarda Alba|La casa de Bernarda Alba]]'' for production in Paris.<ref name=camacho>{{cite book|last=Camacho|first=Enrique, Javier P√©rez Bazo and Manuel Rodr√≠guez Blanco|title=Bu√±uel, 100 a√±os : es peligroso asomarse al interior = Bu√±uel, 100 years : it's dangerous to look inside|year=2001|publisher=Instituto Cervantes / The Museum of Modern Art|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8109-6219-4|pages=83}}</ref> As it turned out, though, before they could both make their way to Europe, they encountered problems in securing the rights from Lorca's family.<ref name=bazin />{{rp|p.21}} While in Mexico City, on a stopover, they had asked √ìscar Dancigers, a Russian √©migr√© producer active in Mexico, for financing.<ref name=camacho /> Dancigers ran an independent production company that specialized in assisting U.S. film studios with on-location shooting in Mexico, but following World War&nbsp;II, he had lost his connection with Hollywood due to his being blacklisted as a Communist.<ref name=schreiber />{{rp|p.73}} Although Dancigers wasn't enthusiastic about the Lorca project, he did want to work with Bu√±uel and persuaded the Spanish director to make a film for him.<ref name="my last sigh" />{{rp|p.197}}
[[File:Libertad Lamarque.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Libertad Lamarque, star of Bu√±uel's first Mexican film. Bu√±uel was said to have held a long-time grudge against Lamarque because the actress was able to bring him to tears when he viewed a "corny melodrama" which she had made in Argentina: "How could I let myself cry over such an absurd, grotesque, ridiculous scene?"<ref name="bill krohn">{{cite book|last1=Krohn|first1=Bill and Paul Duncan|title=Luis Bu√±uel: Cinema 1900‚Äì1983|date=2005|publisher=Taschen|location=Cologne|isbn=978-3822833759}}</ref>{{rp|p.147}}]] The [[Golden Age of Mexican cinema]] was peaking in the mid-to-late 1940s, at just the time Bu√±uel was connecting with Dancigers.<ref name=fein>{{cite journal|last=Fein|first=Seth|title=Hollywood, U.S.-Mexican Relations, and the Devolution of the "Golden Age" of Mexican Cinema|journal=Film-Historia|year=1994|volume=IV|issue=2|pages=103‚Äì135|url=http://161.116.18.149/bibliotecaDigital/cinema/filmhistoria/Art.Fein.pdf|accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref> Movies represented Mexico's third largest industry by 1947, employing 32,000 workers, with 72 film producers who invested 66 million pesos (approximately U.S. $13 million) per year, four active studios with 40 million pesos of invested capital, and approximately 1,500 theaters throughout the nation, with about 200 in Mexico City alone.<ref name=huer>{{cite book|last=Huer|first=Federico|title=La industria cinematogr√°fica mexicana|year=1964|publisher=Policrom√≠a|location=M√©xico. DF|pages=48‚Äì69}}</ref> For their first project, the two men selected what seemed like a sure-fire success, ''[[Gran Casino]]'', a musical [[period piece]] set in [[Tampico]] during the boom years of oil exploitation, starring two of the most popular entertainers in Latin America: [[Libertad Lamarque]], an Argentine actress and singer, and [[Jorge Negrete]], a Mexican singer and leading man in [[Charro#Other uses|"charro" films]].<ref name="Mira Nouselles">{{cite book|last=Mira Nouselles|first=Alberto|title=Historical Dictionary of Spanish Cinema|year=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0-8108-5957-9|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iZm8wWNXeioC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.64}} Bu√±uel recalled: "I kept them singing all the time‚Äîa competition, a championship".<ref name=aranda />{{rp|pp.130‚Äì131}}
The film was not successful at the box office, with some even calling it a fiasco.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Est√®ve|first=Michel|title=Luis Bu√±uel|journal=Etudes Cin√©matographiques|year=1963|issue=20‚Äì21|pages=82}}</ref> Different reasons have been given for its failure with the public; for some, Bu√±uel was forced to make concessions to the bad taste of his stars, particularly Negrete,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mart√≠nez Herranz|first=Amparo|title=Gran Casino de Luis Bu√±uel|journal=Artigrama|year=2002|issue=Num. 17|pages=525}}</ref> others cite Bu√±uel's rusty technical skills<ref name="fuentes discourse">{{cite journal|last=Fuentes|first=V√≠ctor|title=Bu√±uel's Cinematic Narrative and the Latin American New Novel|journal=Discourse|date=Winter‚ÄìSpring 2004 |volume=26|issue=1 & 2|pages=92}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Garc√≠a Riera|first=Emilio|title=Historia documental del cine mexicano. Vol. 3|year=1969|publisher=Era|location=Mexico|isbn=978-968-895-343-3|pages=90}}</ref> and lack of confidence after so many years out of the director's chair,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Charity|first=Tom|title=Luis Bu√±uel: Two-Disc Collector's Edition|journal=Sight and Sound|date=December 2007|volume=17|issue=12|pages=105}}</ref> while still others speculate that Mexican audiences were tiring of genre movies, called "churros", that were perceived as being cheaply and hastily made.<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.48}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mraz|first=John|title=Mexican Cinema: Of churros and charros|journal=Jump Cut|date=February 1984|issue=29|pages=23|url=http://www.ejumpcut.org/archive/onlinessays/JC29folder/MexFilmBook.html}}</ref>
The failure of ''Gran Casino'' sidelined Bu√±uel, and it was over two years before he had the chance to direct another picture.<ref>{{cite book|last=Paranagu√°|first=Paulo Antonio|title=Mexican Cinema|year=1995|publisher=British Film Institute|location=London|isbn=978-0-85170-516-3|pages=202|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U7wuAAAAYAAJ&q=bunuel+gran+casino+failure&dq=bunuel+gran+casino+failure}}</ref> According to Bu√±uel, he spent this time "scratching my nose, watching flies and living off my mother's money",<ref name="my last sigh" />{{rp|p.199}} but he was actually somewhat more industrious than that may sound. With the husband/wife team of Janet and [[Luis Alcoriza]], he wrote the scenario for ''Si usted no puede, yo s√≠'', which was filmed in 1950 by [[Juli√°n Soler]].<ref name=baxter />{{rp|p.203}} He also continued developing the idea for a surrealistic film called ''Ilegible, hijo de flauta'', with the poet [[Juan Larrea (poet)|Juan Larrea]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Gurney|first=Robert|title="Juan Larrea and the Film Bu√±uel Did Not Make", in Companion to Spanish Surrealism, ed. Robert Havard|year=2004|publisher=Tamesis Books|location=Woodbridge, Suffolk|isbn=978-1-85566-104-2|pages=49|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jYOIwLxBLfMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> Dancigers pointed out to him that there was currently a vogue for films about street urchins, so Bu√±uel scoured the back streets and slums of Mexico City in search of material, interviewing social workers about street gang warfare and murdered children.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|pp.203‚Äì204}}
During this period, Dancigers was busy producing films for the actor/director [[Fernando Soler]], one of the most durable of Mexican film personalities, having been referred to as the "national paterfamilias".<ref>{{cite book|last=Stock|first=Ann Marie|title=Framing Latin American Cinema: Contemporary Critical Perspectives|year=1997|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-2972-5|pages=213|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2VFTpFmrV5cC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> Although Soler typically preferred to direct his own films, for their latest collaboration, ''[[El Gran Calavera]]'', based on a play by Adolfo Torrado, he decided that doing both jobs would be too much trouble, so he asked Dancigers to find someone who could be trusted to handle the technical aspects of the directorial duties.<ref name="cine mexicano">{{cite web|title=El gran calavera (1949)|url=http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/gran_calavera.html|website=M√°s de Cien A√±os de Cine Mexicano|publisher=Cine Club ‚Äì Cine Mexicano|accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref> Bu√±uel welcomed the opportunity, stating that: "I amused myself with the montage, the constructions, the angles... All of that interested me because I was still an apprentice in so-called 'normal' cinema."<ref name="cine mexicano" /> As a result of his work on this film, he developed a technique for making films cheaply and quickly by limiting them to 125 shots.<ref name=schreiber />{{rp|p.73}} ''El Gran Calavera'' was completed in 16 days at a cost of 400,000 pesos (approximately $46,000 US at 1948 exchange rates).<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.52}} The picture has been described as "a hilarious screwball send-up of the Mexican [[nouveau riche]]... a wild roller coaster of mistaken identity, sham marriages and misfired suicides",<ref name ="Harvard.edu" /> and it was a big hit at the box office in Mexico.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dent|first=David W.|title=Encyclopedia of Modern Mexico|year=2002|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0-8108-4291-5|pages=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HkiJlXXbAy4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> In 2013, the picture was re-made by Mexican director Gary Alazraki under the title ''[[The Noble Family]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=de las Carreras|first1=Mar√≠a Elena|title=El gran calavera (The Great Madcap, 1949), directed by Luis Bu√±uel|url=https://www.laconservancy.org/sites/default/files/files/GranCalavera_EssayDeLasCarreras.pdf|publisher=The Los Angeles Conservancy|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref> In 1949, Bu√±uel renounced his Spanish citizenship to become a naturalized Mexican.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pulver|first=Andrew|title=A short history of Spanish cinema|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2011/mar/29/short-history-spanish-cinema|work=newEurope|publisher=Guardian News and Media|accessdate=1 September 2012|location=London|date=29 March 2011}}</ref>
The commercial success of ''El Gran Calavera'' enabled Bu√±uel to redeem a promise he had extracted from Dancigers, which was that if Bu√±uel could deliver a money-maker, Dancigers would guarantee "a degree of freedom" on the next film project.<ref name=Doniol-Valcroze /> Knowing that Dancigers was uncomfortable with experimentalism, especially when it might affect the bottom line, Bu√±uel proposed a commercial project titled ''¬°Mi huerfanito jefe!'', about a juvenile street vendor who can't sell his final lottery ticket, which ends up being the winner and making him rich.<ref>{{cite web|title=Los olvidados (1950)|url=http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/olvidados.html|website=Las 100 mejores pel√≠culas del cine mexicano: 2|publisher=Cine Club ‚Äì Cine Mexicano|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref> Dancigers was open to the idea, but instead of a "''[[feuilleton]]''", he suggested making "something rather more serious".<ref name="ibanez and palacio">{{cite book|last=Iba√±ez|first=Juan Carlos and Manuel Palacio|title="Los Olvidados/The Young and the Damned", in The Cinema of Latin America, ed. Alberto Elena and Marina D√≠az L√≥pez|year=2003|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-1-903364-84-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hx5VfnjrGLUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.60}} During his recent researches through the slums of Mexico City, Bu√±uel had read a newspaper account of a twelve-year-old boy's body being found on a garbage dump, and this became the inspiration, and final scene, for the film, called ''[[Los olvidados]]''.<ref name="de la colina" />{{rp|pp.53‚Äì54}}
{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote="The world doesn't work like Hollywood told us it does, and Bu√±uel knew well that poverty's truths could not be window-dressed in any way. This film continues to provoke reactions for its unapologetic portrayal of life without hope or trust. It stands out among Bu√±uel's works as the moment when he broke surface and bellowed, before sinking back into the world of the privileged where his surreal view most loved to play.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pierre|first=DBC|title=The lost boys|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/feb/17/film|work=The Guardian, 16 February 2007|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|accessdate=20 August 2012|location=London|date=16 February 2007}}</ref> |source=[[Booker Prize]] winning author [[DBC Pierre]] on ''Los olvidados''}} The film tells the story of a street gang of children who terrorize their impoverished neighborhood, at one point brutalizing a blind man<ref>{{cite book|last=Villarreal|first=Rachel Kram|title=Gladiolas for the Children of Sanchez: Ernesto P. Uruchurtu's Mexico City, 1950‚Äî1968|year=2008|publisher=ProQuest|location=Ann Arbor MI|pages=31|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LlRhRyTNbqMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|isbn=9781109029550}}</ref> and at another assaulting a legless man who moves around on a dolly, which they toss down a hill.<ref name="ed gonzalez">{{cite web|last=Gonzalez|first=Ed|title=Los Olvidados ****|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/los-olvidados/208|publisher=Slant Magazine|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref> Film historian Carl J. Mora has said of ''Los olvidados'' that the director: "visualized poverty in a radically different way from the traditional forms of Mexican melodrama. Bu√±uel's street children are not 'ennobled' by their desperate struggle for survival; they are in fact ruthless predators who are not better than their equally unromanticized victims".<ref name=mora>{{cite book|last=Mora|first=Carl J.|title=Mexican Cinema: Reflections of a Society|year=1982|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley and Los Angeles|isbn=978-0-520-04304-6}}</ref>{{rp|p.91}} The film was made quickly (18 days) and cheaply (450,000 pesos), with Bu√±uel's fee being the equivalent of $2,000.<ref name=baxter />{{rp|pp.210‚Äì211}} During filming, a number of members of the crew resisted the production in a variety of ways: one technician confronted Bu√±uel and asked why he didn't make a "real" Mexican movie "rather than a miserable picture like this one",<ref name="my last sigh" />{{rp|p.200}} the film's hairdresser quit on the spot over a scene in which the protagonist's mother refuses to give him food ("In Mexico, no mother would say that to her son."),<ref name="mraz nacho lopez">{{cite book|last=Mraz|first=John|title=Nacho Lopez, Mexican Photographer|year=2003|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-4047-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=e4f6kkFbbJQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>{{rp|p.99}} another staff member urged Bu√±uel to abandon shooting on a "garbage heap", noting that there were many "lovely residential neighborhoods like [[Lomas de Chapultepec|Las Lomas]]" that were available,<ref name="mraz nacho lopez" />{{rp|p.99}} while Pedro de Urdimalas, one of the scriptwriters, refused to allow his name in the credits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pedro de Urdimalas|url=http://www.sacm.org.mx/archivos/biografias.asp?txtSocio=08285&offset=0|publisher=Sociedad de Autores y Compositores de M√©xico (SACM)|accessdate=21 August 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506103309/http://www.sacm.org.mx/archivos/biografias.asp?txtSocio=08285&offset=0|archivedate=6 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
[[File:Paz0.jpg|thumb|left|133px|Octavio Paz, ardent champion of ''Los olvidados'' and close friend during Bu√±uel's exile in Mexico<ref>{{cite book|last=Caistor|first=Nick|title=Octavio Paz|year=2007|publisher=Reaktion Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-86189-303-1|page=36|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OkPr_MWp2wMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>]] This hostility was also felt by those who attended the movie's premi√®re in Mexico City on 9 November 1950, when ''Los olvidados'' was taken by many as an insult to Mexican sensibilities and to the Mexican nation.<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.67}} At one point, the audience shrieked in shock as one of the characters looked straight into the camera and hurled a rotten egg at it, leaving a gelatinous, opaque ooze on the lens for a few moments.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Faber|first=Sebastiaan|title=Bu√±uel's Impure Modernism|journal=Modernist Cultures|year=2012|volume=7|issue=1|pages=56‚Äì76|doi=10.3366/mod.2012.0028}}</ref> In his memoir, Bu√±uel recalled that after the initial screening, painter [[Diego Rivera]]'s wife refused to speak to him, while poet [[Le√≥n Felipe]]'s wife had to be restrained physically from attacking him.<ref name="my last sigh" />{{rp|pp.200‚Äì201}} There were even calls to have Bu√±uel's Mexican citizenship revoked.<ref name="de la colina" />{{rp|p.61}} Dancigers, panicked by what he feared would be a complete debacle, quickly commissioned an alternate "happy" ending to the film,<ref name=unesco>{{cite web|title=Nomination Form, Memory of the World Register|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/fileadmin/MULTIMEDIA/HQ/CI/CI/pdf/mow/nomination_forms/los_olvidados.pdf|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> and also tacked on a preface showing stock footage of the skylines of New York, London and Paris with voice-over commentary to the effect that behind the wealth of all the great cities of the world can be found poverty and malnourished children, and that Mexico City "that large modern city, is no exception".<ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=John|title=El Monstruo: Dread and Redemption in Mexico City|year=2009|publisher=Nation Books|location=New York|isbn=978-1-56858-424-9|pages=203|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=psHQERn0VMcC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> Regardless, attendance was so poor that Dancigers withdrew the film after only three days in theaters.<ref name="berg los olvidados">{{cite web|last=Berg|first=Charles Ram√≠rez|title=Los Olvidados (1950)|url=http://www.austinfilm.org/page.aspx?pid=1692|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130414101344/http://www.austinfilm.org/page.aspx?pid=1692|dead-url=yes|archive-date=14 April 2013|website=Essential Cinema|publisher=Austin Film Society|accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref>
Through the determined efforts of future Nobel Prize winner for Literature [[Octavio Paz]], who at the time was in Mexico's diplomatic service, ''Los olvidados'' was chosen to represent Mexico at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] of 1951, and Paz promoted the film assiduously by distributing a supportive manifesto<ref>{{cite news|last=Paz|first=Octavio|title=Cannes, 1951. Los olvidados|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1983/09/29/opinion/433638005_850215.html|accessdate=30 August 2012|newspaper=El Pa√≠s|date=29 September 1983}}</ref> and parading outside the cinema with a placard.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=Jason|title=Octavio Paz, a Study of His Poetics|year=1979|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-22306-5|pages=25|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6wk4AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> Opinion in general was enthusiastic, with the Surrealists (Breton and poet [[Jacques Prevert]]) and other artistic intellectuals (painter [[Marc Chagall]] and poet/dramatist/filmmaker [[Jean Cocteau]]) laudatory, but the communists objected to what they saw as the film's "bourgeois morality" for containing a scene in which the police stop a pederast from assaulting a child.<ref>{{cite web|last=Garmendia|first=Arturo|title=La batalla por "Los Olvidados" de Bu√±uel|url=http://www.cineforever.com/2010/01/27/la-batalla-por-los-olvidados-de-bunuel/|publisher=Cineforever|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> Bu√±uel won the Best Director prize that year at Cannes, and also won the [[International Federation of Film Critics|FIPRESCI International Critics' Award]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Steffen|first=James|title=Los Olvidados|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/93547%7C0/Los-Olvidados.html|website=Turner Classic Movies Film Article|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks}}</ref> After receiving these accolades, the film was reissued in Mexico where it ran for two months to much greater acceptance and profit.<ref>{{cite book|last=Faber|first=Sebastiaan|title=Exile and Cultural Hegemony: Spanish Intellectuals in Mexico, 1939‚Äì1975|year=2002|publisher=Vanderbilt University Press|location=Nashville|isbn=978-0-8265-1422-6|pages=xiv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WAY693mPUWsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> ''Los olvidados'' and its triumph at Cannes made Bu√±uel an instant world celebrity and the most important Spanish-speaking film director in the world.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gazetas|first=Aristides|title=An Introduction to World Cinema|year=2008|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson NC|isbn=978-0-7864-3907-2|pages=198|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CPuZ-2UtVRwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> In 2003, ''Los olvidados'' was recommended by [[UNESCO]] for inclusion in the [[Memory of the World Programme#Memory of the World Register|Memory of the World Register]], calling it: "the most important document in Spanish about the marginal lives of children in contemporary large cities".<ref>{{cite web|title=Los olvidados|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/communication-and-information/flagship-project-activities/memory-of-the-world/register/full-list-of-registered-heritage/registered-heritage-page-5/los-olvidados/|website=Memory of the World|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref>
{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote="Here in Mexico, I have become a professional in the film world. Until I came here I made a film the way a writer makes a book, and on my friends' money at that. I am very grateful and happy to have lived in Mexico, and I have been able to make my films here in a way I could not have in any other country in the world. It is quite true that in the beginning, caught up by necessity, I was forced to make cheap films. But I never made a film which went against my conscience or my convictions. I have never made a superficial, uninteresting film."<ref>{{cite journal|title=Interview with Wilfried Berghahn|journal=Filmkritik|date=1963|issue= 5}}</ref> |source= ‚Äì Luis Bu√±uel on his mid-century career in Mexico. }} Bu√±uel remained in Mexico for the rest of his life, although he spent periods of time filming in France and Spain. In Mexico, he filmed 21 films during an 18-year period. For many critics, although there were occasional widely acknowledged masterpieces like ''Los olvidados'' and [[√âl (film)|''√âl'']] (1953), the majority of his output consisted of generic fare which was adapted to the norms of the national film industry, frequently adopting melodramatic conventions that appealed to local tastes.<ref name=lim>{{cite news|last1=Lim|first1=Dennis|title=Mexican-era Luis Bu√±uel|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/feb/08/entertainment/ca-secondlook8|accessdate=20 September 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=8 February 2009}}</ref> Other commentators, however, have written of the deceptive complexity and intensity of many of these films, arguing that, collectively, they, "bring a philosophical depth and power to his cinema, together offering a sustained meditation on ideas of religion, class inequity, violence and desire."<ref name ="Harvard.edu" /> Although Bu√±uel usually had little choice regarding the selection of these projects,<ref name=Delmas>{{cite journal|last1=Delmas|first1=Jean|title=Bu√±uel, Citizen of Mexico|journal=Jeune Cinema|date=February 1966|issue= 12}}</ref> they often deal with themes that were central to his lifelong concerns:<ref name=adler>{{cite news|last1=Adler|first1=Renata|title=Screen: Bunuel's Relentless 'Nazarin':Film Set in the Mexico of Porfirio Diaz|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C02E1D7163AE134BC4951DFB0668383679EDE|accessdate=27 September 2014|work=New York Times|agency=The New York Times Company|date=21 June 1968}}</ref> * sexual pathology:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gutierrez-Albill|first1=Julian Daniel|title=Queering Bu√±uel: Sexual Dissidence and Psychoanalysis in His Mexican and Spanish Cinema|date=2008|publisher=I.B.Tauris|location=London|isbn=9781845116682|pages=59‚Äì62|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E38AAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> ''√âl'' (1953), ''[[Ensayo de un crimen]]'' (1955), and ''[[Wuthering Heights (1954 film)|Abismos de pasi√≥n]]'' (1954) *the destructive effects of rampant [[machismo]]:<ref>{{cite book|last1=Evans|first1=Peter William|title=The Films of Luis Bu√±uel. Subjectivity and Desire|date=1995|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0198159063|page=143}}</ref> ''[[El Bruto]]'', (1953), ''[[El r√≠o y la muerte]]'', (1955); *the blurring of fantasy and reality:<ref>{{cite web|title=Luis Bu√±uel's Cinema of Entrapment in the Age of Cowardice: The Search for a Greater Truth|url=http://users.hal-pc.org/~questers/JAVA/fire/Bunuel.html|publisher=Gregory and Maria Pearse|accessdate=27 September 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402034318/http://users.hal-pc.org/~questers/JAVA/fire/Bunuel.html|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[Subida al cielo]]'' (1952), ''[[La ilusi√≥n viaja en tranv√≠a]]'' (1954); *the disruptive status of women in a male-dominated culture:<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mu√±oz|first1=Sara|title=La construcci√≥n femenina en el discurso cinematogr√°fico de Bu√±uel: la femme fatale|url=http://www.hispanetjournal.com/4Surrealfemme-EDITADO.pdf|website=Hispanet Journal 2|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> ''[[Susana (film)|Susana]]'' (1951), ''[[La hija del enga√±o]]'' (1951‚Äîa remake of the Film√≥fono production ''Don Quint√≠n el amargao'' of 16 years earlier),<ref>{{cite web|title=La hija del enga√±o (1951)|url=http://cinemexicano.mty.itesm.mx/peliculas/hija_enganio.html|website=M√°s de Cien A√±os de Cine Mexicano|publisher=Maximiliano Maza|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref> ''[[Una mujer sin amor]]'' (1952); and *the absurdity of the religious life:<ref name=edwards />{{rp|pp.118‚Äì19}} ''[[Nazar√≠n]]'' (1959) and ''Sim√≥n del desierto'' (1965).
As busy as he was during the 1950s and early 1960s, there were still many film projects that Bu√±uel had to abandon due to lack of financing or studio support, including a cherished plan to film Mexican novelist [[Juan Rulfo]]'s ''[[Pedro P√°ramo]]'', of which he said how much he enjoyed "the crossing from the mysterious to the real, almost without transition. I really like this mixture of reality and fantasy, but I don't know how to bring it to the screen."<ref>{{cite book|last=Poniatowska|first=Elena|title=Palabras cruzadas|year=1961|publisher=Ediciones Era|location=Mexico City|pages=191}}</ref> Other unrealized projects during his lifetime included adaptations of [[Andr√© Gide]]'s ''Les caves du Vatican''; [[Benito P√©rez Gald√≥s]]'s ''[[Fortunata y Jacinta]]'', ''[[Do√±a Perfecta]]'', and ''√Ångel Guerra''; [[Evelyn Waugh]]'s ''[[The Loved One]]''; [[William Golding]]'s ''[[Lord of the Flies]]''; [[Dalton Trumbo]]'s ''[[Johnny Got His Gun]]''; [[J. K. Huysmans]]' ''[[L√†-bas (novel)|L√†-Bas]]''; [[Matthew Lewis (writer)|Matthew Lewis]]'s ''[[The Monk]]''; [[Jos√© Donoso]]'s ''[[Hell Has No Limits|Lugar sin l√≠mites]]''; a film of four stories based on [[Carlos Fuentes]]'s ''[[Aura (Fuentes)|Aura]]''; and [[Julio Cort√°zar]]'s ''[[Final del juego|Las m√©nades]]''.<ref name="fuentes discourse" />{{rp|p.96}} Some of these adaptations were later used by following directors.
====Mexico and beyond: return to international filmmaking (1954‚Äì1960)==== [[File:S.Kragujevic, G√©rard Philipe 1955.JPG|thumb|175px|[[G√©rard Philipe]], popular French star of Bu√±uel's ''[[La Fi√®vre Monte √† El Pao]]''. At one point during the filming, Bu√±uel asked Philipe, who was visibly dying of cancer, why the actor was making this film, and Philipe responded by asking the director the same question, to which both said they didn't know.<ref name=hagopian>{{cite web|last1=Hagopian|first1=Kevin|title=Fever Mounts in El Pao|url=http://www.albany.edu/writers-inst/webpages4/filmnotes/fnf02n11.html|website=New York State Writers Institute|publisher=Writers Institute|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>]] As much as he welcomed steady employment in the Mexican film industry, Bu√±uel was quick to seize opportunities to re-emerge onto the international film scene and to engage with themes that were not necessarily focused on Mexican preoccupations.<ref name=acevedo-munoz />{{rp|p.144}} His first chance came in 1954, when Dancigers partnered with Henry F. Ehrlich, of [[United Artists]], to co-produce a film version of [[Daniel Defoe]]'s ''[[Robinson Crusoe]]'', using a script developed by the Canadian writer [[Hugo Butler]]. The film was produced by George Pepper, the former executive secretary of the Hollywood Democratic Committee. Both Butler and Pepper were emigres from Hollywood who had run afoul of authorities seeking out communists.<ref name=schreiber />{{rp|p.75}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsdefrance.com/review/the-young-one-1960.html|title=Review of the film The Young One (1960)|first=James|last=Travers|date=27 October 2017|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref> The result, ''[[Adventures of Robinson Crusoe]]'', was Bu√±uel's first color film.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=The Adventures of Robinson Crusoe|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-adventures-of-robinson-crusoe|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref> Bu√±uel was given much more time than usual for the filming (three months), which was accomplished on location in Manzanillo, a Pacific seaport with a lush jungle interior, and was shot simultaneously in English and Spanish.<ref name="axmaker robinson crusoe">{{cite web|last1=Axmaker|first1=Sean|title=Adventures of Robinson Crusoe (1954)|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/66823/Adventures-of-Robinson-Crusoe/articles.html|website=Turner Classic Movies|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref> When the film was released in the United States, its young star [[Dan O'Herlihy]] used his own money to fund a Los Angeles run for the film and gave free admission to all members of the [[Screen Actors Guild]], who in turn rewarded the little-known actor with his only [[Oscar award|Oscar]] nomination.<ref name="axmaker robinson crusoe" />
In the mid-1950s, Bu√±uel got the chance to work again in France on international co-productions. The result was what critic [[Raymond Durgnat]] has called the director's "revolutionary triptych", in that each of the three films is "openly, or by implication, a study in the morality and tactics of armed revolution against a right-wing dictatorship."<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.100}} The first, ''[[Cela s'appelle l'aurore]]'' (Franco-Italian, 1956) required Bu√±uel and the [['Pataphysics|"pataphysical"]] writer [[Jean Ferry]] to adapt a novel by [[Emmanuel Robl√®s]] after the celebrated writer [[Jean Genet]] failed to deliver a script after having been paid in full.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.100}} The second film was [[Death in the Garden|''La Mort en ce jardin'']] (Franco-Mexican, 1956), which was adapted by Bu√±uel and his frequent collaborator [[Luis Alcoriza]] from a novel by the Belgian writer [[Jos√©-Andr√© Lacour]]. The final part of the "triptych" was ''[[La Fi√®vre Monte √† El Pao]]'' (Franco-Mexican, 1959), the last film of the popular French star [[G√©rard Philipe]], who died in the final stages of the production.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Canby|first1=Vincent|title=Film: From Bunuel, 'Los Ambiciosos,' at the Public|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/02/12/movies/film-from-bunuel-los-ambiciosos-at-the-public.html|accessdate=30 September 2014|agency=New York Times|date=12 February 1988}}</ref> Bu√±uel was later to explain that he was so strapped for cash that he, "took everything that was offered to me, as long as it wasn't humiliating."<ref name=hagopian />
In 1960, Bu√±uel re-teamed with scenarist Hugo Butler and organizer George Pepper, allegedly his favorite producer, to make his second English-language film, a US/Mexico co-production called ''[[The Young One]]'', based on a short story by writer and former CIA-agent [[Peter Matthiessen]].<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=hZuzxKQfhYUC&pg=PA191&lpg=PA191&dq=george+pepper+Bu√±uel#v=onepage&q=pepper | title=My Last Sigh: The Autobiography of Luis Bunuel| isbn=9780345803719| last1=Bunuel| first1=Luis| date=2013-03-26}}</ref> This film has been called "a surprisingly uncompromising study of racism and sexual desire, set on a remote island in the Deep South"<ref name ="Harvard.edu" /> and has been described by critic Ed Gonzalez as, "salacious enough to make [[Elia Kazan]]'s [[Baby Doll]] and [[Louis Malle|Luis Malle's]] [[Pretty Baby (1978 film)|''Pretty Baby'']] blush."<ref name="The Young One 4 out of 4">{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=The Young One 4 out of 4|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-young-one|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref> Although the film won a special award at the Cannes Film Festival for its treatment of racial discrimination,<ref name=bentley />{{rp|p.151}} the US critics were so hostile upon its release that Bu√±uel was later to say that, "a Harlem newspaper even wrote that I should be hung upside down from a lamppost on Fifth Avenue....I made this film with love, but it never had a chance."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rosenbaum|first1=Jonathan|title=The Young One: Bu√±uel's Neglected Masterpiece|url=http://www.jonathanrosenbaum.net/2009/07/22909/|website=jonathanrosenbaum.net|accessdate=30 September 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006084401/http://www.jonathanrosenbaum.net/2009/07/22909/|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the words of film historian Peter Harcourt: "if ''The Young One'' must still be considered a 'bad' film by conventional standards, then it is one of the most subtle, most challenging and most distinguished bad films ever made."<ref name="peter harcourt">{{cite journal|last1=Harcourt|first1=Peter|title=Luis Bu√±uel: Spaniard and Surrealist|journal=Film Quarterly|date=Spring 1967|volume=20|issue=3|page=12|url=http://www.austinlibrary.com:2138/stable/pdfplus/1210106.pdf?acceptTC=true&jpdConfirm=true|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>
===Late international period (1961‚Äì1977)=== [[File:Silvia Pinal (1970).jpg|thumb|200px|left|[[Silvia Pinal]] starred in ''Viridiana'' (1961). She was re-united with Bu√±uel again, starring in ''El √°ngel exterminador'' (1962) and in ''Sim√≥n del desierto'' (1964). Pinal is pictured here in 1970.]]
At the 1960 Cannes Festival, Bu√±uel was approached by the young director [[Carlos Saura]], whose film [[The Delinquents (1960 film)|''Los Golfos'']] had been entered officially to represent Spain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Los Golfos|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/3299/year/1960.html|publisher=Festival de Cannes|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref> Two years earlier, Saura had partnered with [[Juan Antonio Bardem]] and [[Luis Garc√≠a Berlanga]] to form a production company called UNINCI,<ref name="andrew whittaker">{{cite book|last1=Whittaker|first1=Andrew|title=Speak the Culture: Spain: Be Fluent in Spanish Life and Culture|date=2008|publisher=Thorogood Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1854186058|page=225|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2rZS8SWMroUC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref> and the group was keen to get Bu√±uel to make a new film in his native country as part of their overall goal of creating a uniquely Spanish brand of cinema.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.190‚Äì91}} At the same time, Mexican actress [[Silvia Pinal]] was eager to work with Bu√±uel and talked her producer-husband [[Gustavo Alatriste]] into providing additional funding for the project with the understanding that the director, who Pinal described as "a man worshiped and idolized", would be given "absolute freedom" in carrying out the work.<ref name="agustin de gracia">{{cite news|last1=de Gracia|first1=Agust√≠n|title=Recuerdan a Luis Bu√±uel a 30 a√±os de su fallecimiento|url=http://www.laopinion.com/entretenimientocine/article/20130731/Recuerdan-a-Luis-Bunuel-a-30-anos-de-su-fallecimiento&template=print|accessdate=4 October 2014|work=laopinion.com|date=31 July 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006094142/http://www.laopinion.com/entretenimientocine/article/20130731/Recuerdan-a-Luis-Bunuel-a-30-anos-de-su-fallecimiento%26template%3Dprint|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Finally, Bu√±uel agreed to work again in Spain when further support was provided by producer [[Pere Portabella]]'s company ''Film 59''.<ref name="pere portabella">{{cite web|title=Pere Portabella|url=http://www.moma.org/visit/calendar/films/556|website=Film Exhibitions|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>
Bu√±uel and his co-scenarist [[Julio Alejandro]] drafted a preliminary screenplay for ''[[Viridiana]]'', which critic [[Andrew Sarris]] has described as incorporating "a plot which is almost too lurid to synopsize even in these enlightened times",<ref name="sarris viridiana">{{cite web|last1=Sarris|first1=Andrew|title=The Devil and the Nun|url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/film/movie/contents/the_devil_and_the_nun_sarris.pdf|website=warwick.ac.uk|publisher=University of Warwick|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> dealing with rape, incest, hints of necrophilia, animal cruelty and sacrilege, and dutifully submitted it to the Spanish censor, who, to the surprise of nearly everyone, approved it after requesting only minor modifications and one significant change to the ending.<ref name="d'lugo films of carlos saura">{{cite book|last1=D'Lugo|first1=Marvin|title=The Films of Carlos Saura: The Practice of Seeing|date=1991|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton, NJ|isbn=978-0-691-03142-2|pages=42‚Äì43|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RUAks4YGLWAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Although Bu√±uel accommodated the censor's demands, he came up with a final scene that was even more provocative than the scene it replaced: "even more immoral", as Bu√±uel was later to observe.<ref name="ebert viridiana">{{cite web|last1=Ebert|first1=Roger|title=Viridiana|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-viridiana-1961|website=The Great Movies|publisher=RogerEbert.com|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Since Bu√±uel had more than adequate resources, top-flight technical and artistic crews, and experienced actors, filming of ''Viridiana'' (which took place on location and at Bardem's studios in Madrid) went smoothly and quickly.<ref name=Pavlovi>{{cite book|last=Pavloviƒá|first=Tatjana|title=100 Years of Spanish Cinema|year=2009|publisher=Wiley|location=New York|isbn=978-1-4051-8419-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PtFXpxyWMi4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|display-authors=etal}}</ref>{{rp|p. 98}}
Bu√±uel submitted a cutting copy to the censors and then arranged for his son, Juan Luis, to smuggle the negatives to Paris for the final editing and mixing,<ref>{{cite web|title=Viridiana.50|url=http://www.viridiana50.com/uninci.php|website=viridiana50.com|publisher=Ministerio de Cultura de Espa√±a|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> ensuring that the authorities would not have an opportunity to view the finished product before its planned submission as Spain's official entry to the 1961 Cannes Festival.<ref name=buache>{{cite book|last1=Buache|first1=Freddy|title=The Cinema of Luis Bu√±uel|date=1973|publisher=Tantivy Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-498-01302-7|pages=117‚Äì20}}</ref> Spain's director general of cinematography Jos√© Munoz-Fontan presented the film on the last day of the festival and then, on the urging of Portabella and Bardem, appeared in person to accept the top prize, the [[Palme d'Or]], which the film shared with the French entry ''[[Une aussi longue absence]]'', directed by [[Henri Colpi]].<ref name="buache french edition">{{cite book|last1=Buache|first1=Freddy|title=Bu√±uel|date=1975|publisher=L'Age d'Homme| location=Lausanne| isbn=9782825133415| page=119| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tuo1JTpoxQAC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> Within days, ''[[l'Osservatore Romano]]'', the Vatican's official organ, denounced the film as an insult not only to Catholicism but to Christianity in general.<ref name=malcolm>{{cite news|last1=Malcolm|first1=Derek|title=Luis Bu√±uel: Viridiana|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/1999/apr/01/derekmalcolmscenturyoffilm.derekmalcolm|accessdate=5 October 2014|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=1 April 1999}}</ref> Consequences to nearly all concerned were swift: Munoz-Fontan was cashiered from his government post,<ref name="buache french edition" /> the film was banned in Spain for the next 17 years, all mention of it in the press was prohibited, and the two Spanish production companies UNINCI and ''Film 59'' were disbanded.<ref name="d'lugo films of carlos saura" />
[[File:Jean-Claude Carri√®re √† la BNF.jpg|thumb|right|270px|"When today I amuse myself by making useless calculations, I realize that Bu√±uel and I shared more than two thousand meals together and that on more than fifteen hundred occasions he knocked on my door, notes in hand, ready to begin work. I'm not even counting the walks, the drinks, the films we watched together, the film festivals."<ref name="carriere flickhead">{{cite web|title=Luis Bu√±uel Remembered by Jean-Claude Carri√®re|url=http://home.comcast.net/~flickhead/Luis-Bunuel.html|website=Flickhead|publisher=Jean-Claude Carri√®re|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> ‚Äì Jean-Claude Carri√®re on his long-term collaboration with Bu√±uel.]] Bu√±uel went on to make two more films in Mexico with Pinal and Alatriste, ''[[El √°ngel exterminador]]'' (1962) and ''[[Sim√≥n del desierto]]'' (1965)‚Äî along with ''Viridiana'', they form the so-called "Bu√±uelian trilogy" ‚Äî and was later to say that Alatriste had been the one producer who gave him the most freedom in creative expression.<ref name="Rowman & Littlefield">{{cite book|last1=Alfaro|first1=Eduardo de la Vega|title="The Decline of the Golden Age and the Making of the Crisis," in Mexico's Cinema: A Century of Film and Filmmakers, edited by Joanne Hershfield and David R. Maciel|date=1999|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0842026826|page=189}}</ref>
In 1963, actor [[Fernando Rey]], one of the stars of ''Viridiana'', introduced Bu√±uel to producer [[Serge Silberman]], a Polish entrepreneur who had fled to Paris when his family died in the Holocaust<ref>{{cite news|title=Serge Silberman, productor de Luis Bu√±uel y de Akira Kurosawa|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2003/07/25/agenda/1059084008_850215.html|accessdate=13 October 2014|work=El Pais|agency=http://elpais.com/|date=25 July 2003}}</ref> and had worked with several renowned French directors, including [[Jean-Pierre Melville]], [[Jacques Becker]], [[Marcel Camus]] and [[Christian-Jaque]].<ref name="ronald bergan">{{cite news|last1=Bergan|first1=Ronald|title=Serge Silberman: Flamboyant film producer prepared to go out on a limb|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2003/jul/28/guardianobituaries.filmnews|accessdate=13 October 2014|work=The Guardian,|agency=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=27 July 2003}}</ref> Silberman proposed that the two make an adaptation of [[Octave Mirbeau]]'s [[The Diary of a Chambermaid (novel)|''Journal d'une femme de chambre'']], which Bu√±uel had read several times.<ref name="gonzalez chambermaid">{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=The Diary of a Chambermaid|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-diary-of-a-chambermaid|website=Slant Magazine.|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> Bu√±uel wanted to do the filming in Mexico with Pinal, but Silberman insisted it be done in France.<ref name="gonzalez chambermaid" />
Pinal was so determined to work again with Bu√±uel that she was ready to move to France, learn the language and even work for nothing in order to get the part of [[C√©lestine (Mirbeau)|C√©lestine]], the title character.<ref name="rivera pinal">{{cite journal|last1=Rivera J.|first1=H√©ctor|title=Las experiencias de Silvia Pinal con Bu√±uel y Gustavo Alatriste|journal=Proceso|date=13 July 1997|issue=n1080|page=62}}</ref> Silberman, however, wanted French actress [[Jeanne Moreau]] to play the role, so he put Pinal off by telling her that Moreau, too, was willing to act with no fee. Ultimately, Silberman got his way, leaving Pinal so disappointed that she was later to claim that Alatriste's failure to help her secure this part led to the breakup of their marriage.<ref name="rivera pinal" /> When Bu√±uel requested a French-speaking writer with whom to collaborate on the screenplay, Silberman suggested the 32-year-old [[Jean-Claude Carri√®re]], an actor whose previous screenwriting credits included only a few films for the comic star/director [[Pierre √âtaix]], but once Bu√±uel learned that Carri√®re was the scion of a wine-growing family, the newcomer was hired on the spot.<ref name="ronald bergan" /> At first, Carri√®re found it difficult to work with Bu√±uel, because the young man was so deferential to the famous director that he never challenged any of Bu√±uel's ideas, until, at Bu√±uel's covert insistence, Silberman told Carri√®re to stand up to Bu√±uel now and then; as Carri√®re was later to say: "In a way, Bu√±uel needed an opponent. He didn't need a secretary ‚Äì he needed someone to contradict him and oppose him and to make suggestions."<ref name="tim grierson FilmCraft: Screenwriting">{{cite book|last1=Grierson|first1=Tim|title=FilmCraft: Screenwriting|date=2013|publisher=Focal Press|location=Burlington MA|isbn=978-0240824864|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PHtiAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> The finished 1964 film, [[Diary of a Chambermaid (1964 film)|''Diary of a Chambermaid'']], became the first of several to be made by the team of Bu√±uel, Carri√®re and Silberman. Carri√®re was later to say: "Without me and without Serge Silberman, the producer, perhaps Bu√±uel would not have made so many films after he was 65. We really encouraged him to work. That's for sure."<ref name=Colville-Andersen>{{cite web|last1=Colville-Andersen|first1=Mikael|title=The Storytellers ‚Äì Interview with Jean-Claude Carri√©r√©|url=http://zakka.dk/euroscreenwriters/screenwriters/jean-claude_carriere.htm|website=Zakkatography|publisher=Colville-Andersen.|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> This was the second attempt to film Mirbeau's novel, the first being [[The Diary of a Chambermaid (1946 film)|a 1946 Hollywood production]] directed by [[Jean Renoir]], which Bu√±uel refused to view for fear of being influenced by the famous French director, whom he venerated.<ref name="david kalat">{{cite web|last1=Kalat|first1=David|title=Diary of a Chambermaid|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/474221%7C474228/Diary-of-a-Chambermaid.html|website=Turner Classic Movies|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> Bu√±uel's version, while admired by many, has often been compared unfavorably to Renoir's, with a number of critics claiming that Renoir's ''Diary'' fits better in Renoir's overall ''oeuvre'', while Bu√±uel's ''Diary'' is not sufficiently "Bu√±uelian".<ref name="Geoffrey T. Harris">{{cite book|last1=Harris|first1=Geoffrey T.|title=On Translating French Literature and Film, Volume 1|date=1996|publisher=Rodopi|location=Amsterdam|isbn=978-90-5183-933-3|page=92|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wUbGJ8kozAoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref>
After the 1964 release of ''Diary'', Bu√±uel again tried to make a film of Matthew Lewis' ''[[The Monk]]'', a project on which he had worked, on and off, since 1938, according to producer [[Pierre Braunberger]].<ref name=gubern />{{rp|p.137}} He and Carri√®re wrote a screenplay, but were unable to obtain funding for the project, which would be finally realized in 1973 under the direction of Bu√±uel devotee [[Adonis A. Kyrou|Ado Kyrou]], with considerable assistance from both Bu√±uel and Carri√®re.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Aspley|first1=Keith|title=Historical Dictionary of Surrealism|date=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham MD|isbn=978-0810858473|page=284|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3KK7JHqNrRsC&pg=PA284&dq=bunuel+the+monk+lewis+carriere#v=onepage&q=bunuel%20the%20monk%20lewis%20carriere|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref>
In 1965, Bu√±uel manage to work again with Sylvia Pinal in what would turn out to be his last Mexican feature, co-starring Claudio Brook, ''[[Sim√≥n del desierto]]''.<ref name="Rowman & Littlefield"/> Pinal was keenly interested in continuing to work with Bu√±uel, trusting him completely and frequently stating that he brought out the best in her; however, this would be their last collaboration.<ref name="La Jornada">{{cite news|title=No he conocido a alguien que supere a Luis Bu√±uel: Silvia Pinal|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2013/07/29/espectaculos/a12n1esp|accessdate=13 October 2014|work=La Jornada|agency=DEMOS, Desarrollo de Medios,|date=29 July 2013}}</ref>
[[File:Catherine Deneuve 1968.jpg|thumb|195px|left|Catherine Deneuve starred in ''[[Belle de Jour (film)|Belle de Jour]]'' (1967), based on Joseph Kessel's novel, playing the role of a bored upper class Parisian housewife who spends her weekdays in a brothel. She was re-united with Bu√±uel again, starring in ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'' (1970), shot in [[Toledo, Spain]]. Deneuve is pictured here in 1968]] {{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote="Well, I think it was difficult for him, coping with his deafness. Some people said he was not that deaf, but I think, when you don't hear very well and when you're tired, everything sinks into a buzz, and it is very hard. French is not his language, so on ''Belle de Jour'', I'm sure that it was much more of an effort for him to have to explain. ".<ref name=zohn /> |source=Actress [[Catherine Deneuve]], star of ''Belle de Jour''}}
In 1966, Bu√±uel was approached by [[Robert and Raymond Hakim|the Hakim brothers, Robert and Raymond]], Egyptian-French producers who specialized in sexy films directed by star filmmakers,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bernard|first1=Jami|title=The X-List: The National Society of Film Critics' Guide to the Movies that Turn Us On|date=2005|publisher=Da Capo Press|location=Cambridge MA|isbn=978-0306814457|page=40|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pWH97tY1KfMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> who offered him the opportunity to direct a film version of [[Joseph Kessel]]'s novel [[Belle de Jour (novel)|''Belle de Jour'']], a book about an affluent young woman who leads a double life as a prostitute, and that had caused a scandal upon its first publication in 1928.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Boucharenc|first1=Myriam|title=L'√©crivain-reporter au c≈ìur des ann√©es trente|date=2004|publisher=Presses Univ. Septentrion|location=Lille|isbn=978-2-85939-842-2|page=184|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2GShcPJaDg4C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> Bu√±uel did not like Kessel's novel, considering it "a bit of a soap opera",<ref name="Europe of Cultures">{{cite web|last1=Durieux|first1=Christian|title=Conversation with Luis Bu√±uel on Belle de jour|url=http://fresques.ina.fr/europe-des-cultures-en/fiche-media/Europe00048/conversation-with-luis-bunuel-on-belle-de-jour.html|website=Europe of Cultures|publisher=INA Institute|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> but he took on the challenge because: "I found it interesting to try to turn something I didn't like into something I did."<ref name="levy belle de jour">{{cite web|last1=Levy|first1=Emanuel|title=Belle de Jour (1967): Bunuel's Masterpiece Starring Catherine Deneuve|url=http://emanuellevy.com/pick-of-the-week/belle-de-jour-1967-bunuels-masterpiece-starring-catherine-deneuve/|website=Cinema 24/7|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> So he and Carri√®re set out enthusiastically to interview women in the brothels of Madrid to learn about their sexual fantasies.<ref name="belle de jour tcm">{{cite web|last=Landazuri|first=Margarita|title=Belle de jour|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article.html?id=628630%7C636738|website=TCM Classic Movies|publisher=Turner Entertainment Networks|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref> Bu√±uel also was not happy about the choice of the 22-year-old [[Catherine Deneuve]] for the title role, feeling that she had been foisted upon him by the Hakim brothers and Deneuve's lover at the time, director [[Fran√ßois Truffaut]].<ref name="moma belle de jour">{{cite web|last1=Silver|first1=Charles|title=Luis Bu√±uel's Belle de Jour|url=http://www.moma.org/explore/inside_out/2014/04/22/luis-bunuels-belle-de-jour/|website=Inside/Out|publisher=Museum of Modern Art|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> As a result, both actress and director found working together difficult, with Deneuve claiming, "I felt they showed more of me than they'd said they were going to. There were moments when I felt totally used. I was very unhappy,"<ref name="anderson belle">{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Melissa|title=Belle de jour: Tough Love|url=http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/2121-belle-de-jour-tough-love|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> and Bu√±uel deriding her prudery on the set and complaining that the hairdresser had to bind her breasts in order to assure her that they would not show on screen.<ref name=zohn>{{cite web|last1=Zohn|first1=Patricia|title=Belle de Jour: Catherine Deneuve and Her Shades of Grey |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/patricia-zohn/catherine-deneuve_b_1395172.html|website=HuffPost Arts and Culture| publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> The resulting film has been described by film critic [[Roger Ebert]] as "possibly the best-known erotic film of modern times, perhaps the best",<ref>{{cite web| last1=Ebert| first1=Roger| title=Belle de Jour|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-belle-de-jour-1967|website=Great Movies|publisher=Roger Ebert.com|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> even though, as another critic has written, "in terms of explicit sexual activity, there is little in ''Belle de jour'' we might not see in a [[Doris Day]] comedy from the same year".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Melville|first1=David|title=Who Let the Cats Out? Bu√±uel, Deneuve and Belle de jour|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2013/cteq/who-let-the-cats-out-bunuel-deneuve-and-belle-de-jour/|website=Senses of Cinema|publisher=Film Victoria|accessdate=29 October 2014}}</ref> It was Bu√±uel's most successful film at the box office.<ref name="anderson belle" />
Critics have noted Bu√±uel's habit of following up a commercial or critical success with a more personal, idiosyncratic film that might have less chance of popular esteem.<ref name="Polizzotti milky way">{{cite web|last1=Polizzotti|first1=Mark| title=The Milky Way: Easy Striders|url=http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/611-the-milky-way-easy-striders|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>
After the worldwide success of his 1967 ''Belle de jour'', and upon viewing [[Jean-Luc Godard]]'s film ''La Chinoise'', Bu√±uel, who had wanted to make a film about Catholic heresies for years, told Carri√®re: "If that is what today's cinema is like, then we can make a film about heresies."<ref name="supernal dreams">{{cite web| last1=French| first1=Lawrence| title=Supernal Dreams: Jean-Claude Carriere on Luis Bunuel's Sublime Fantasy, "The Milky Way" | url=http://cinefantastiqueonline.com/2009/02/supernal-dreams-jean-claude-carriere-on-luis-bunuels-sublime-fantasy-the-milky-way/|website=Cinefantastique Online|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> The two spent months researching Catholic history and created the 1969 film [[The Milky Way (1969 film)|''The Milky Way'']], a "picaresque road film"<ref name=Nochimson>{{cite book|last1=Nochimson|first1=Martha|title=World on Film: An Introduction| date=2010| publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=New York|isbn=978-1405139793|page=294|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DXK5gkQwAs8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> that tells the story of two vagabonds on [[Camino de Santiago|pilgrimage to the tomb of the Apostle James]] at [[Santiago de Compostela]], during which they travel through time and space to take part in situations illustrating heresies that arose from the six major Catholic dogmas.<ref name=mazur>{{cite book|last1=Mazur|first1=Eric Michael|title=Encyclopedia of Religion and Film|date=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, CA|isbn=978-0313330728|page=101|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JPNfox6H5qwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> [[Vincent Canby]], reviewing the film in the ''New York Times'', compared it to [[George Stevens]]' blockbuster ''[[The Greatest Story Ever Told]]'', in that Bu√±uel had made a film about Jesus casting nearly all the famous French performers of the time in cameo roles.<ref>{{cite news| last1=Canby| first1=Vincent|title='The Milky Way':Bunuel Weaves Surreal Spiritual Journey|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=990CE5D8123AE03BBC4F51DFB766838B669EDE|accessdate=11 December 2014|work=New York Times|date=27 January 1970}}</ref> ''The Milky Way'' was banned in Italy, only to have the Catholic Church intervene on its behalf.<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.152}}
{{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote=A few great directors have the ability to draw us into their dream world, into their personalities and obsessions and fascinate us with them for a short time. This is the highest level of escapism the movies can provide for us ‚Äì just as our elementary identification with a hero or a heroine was the lowest.<ref name=zohn /> |source=Film critic [[Roger Ebert]], on ''Tristana''<ref name="ebert tristana">{{cite web|last1=Ebert|first1=Roger|title=Tristana|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/tristana-1970|website=Roger Ebert.com| publisher=Ebert Digital LLC|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref>}}
The 1970 film ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'' is a film about a young woman who is seduced and manipulated by her guardian, who attempts to thwart her romance with a young artist and who eventually induces her to marry him after she loses one of her legs due to a tumor. It has been considered by scholar Beth Miller the least understood of Bu√±uel's films, and consequently one of the most underrated, due to a "consistent failure to apprehend its political and, especially, its socialist-feminist statement".<ref name="beth miller">{{cite book|last1=Miller|first1=Beth|title="From Mistress to Murderess," in Women in Hispanic Literature: Icons and Fallen Idols, edited by Beth Kurti Miller|date=1983|publisher=University of California Press| isbn=978-0520043671| pages=340‚Äì41|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8cCIcUaEznYC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> Bu√±uel had wanted to make a film of [[Benito P√©rez Gald√≥s]]' novel ''[[Tristana (novel)|Tristana]]'' as early as 1952, even though he considered Gald√≥s' book the author's weakest, in Bu√±uel's words: "of the 'I love you, my little pigeon' genre, very kitsch".<ref name=fujiwara>{{cite web|last1=Fujiwara|first1=Chris|title=Tristana|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article.html?isPreview=&id=628630%7C449958&name=Tristana|website=TCM Summer Under the Stars|publisher=Turner Entertainment Network|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> After finishing ''Viridiana'' and in the wake of the scandal its release caused in 1962, the Spanish censor flatly turned down this project,<ref name=durgnat />{{rp|p.152}} and Bu√±uel had to wait for 8 years before he could receive backing from the Spanish production company Epoca Films.<ref name=fujiwara /> The censors had threatened to deny permission for the film on the grounds that it encouraged duelling, so Bu√±uel had to approach the subject matter very gingerly, in addition to making concessions to his French/Italian/Spanish producers, who insisted on casting two of the three primary roles with actors not of Bu√±uel's choosing: [[Franco Nero]] and Catherine Deneuve.<ref name="faulkner literary adaptations" />{{rp|p.128}} On this occasion, however, Deneuve and Bu√±uel had a more mutually satisfactory working relationship, with Deneuve telling an interviewer, "but in the end, you know, it was actually rather a wonderful shoot. ''Tristana'' is one of my favorite films. Personally, as an actress, I prefer ''Tristana'' to ''Belle de Jour''."<ref name=fujiwara />
The germ of the idea for their next film together, ''[[The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie]]'' (1972) came from Bu√±uel and Serge Silberman discussing uncanny repetition in everyday life; Silberman told an anecdote about how he had invited some friends for dinner at his house, only to forget about it, so that, on the night of the dinner party, he was absent and his wife was in her nightclothes.<ref name=pinkos>{{cite web| last1=Pinkos| first1=Jefferey| title=Dinner Is Served| url=http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeoisie/| website=Lone Star Film Society| accessdate=12 December 2014| deadurl=yes| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223031928/http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeoisie/| archivedate=23 December 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film tells of a group of affluent friends who are continually stymied in their attempts to eat a meal together, a situation that a number of critics have contrasted to the opposite dilemma of the characters in ''The Exterminating Angel'', where guests of a dinner party are mysteriously unable to leave after having completed their meal.<ref name=lim /> For this film, Bu√±uel, Silberman and Carri√®re assembled a top-flight cast of European performers, "a veritable rogues' gallery of French art-house cinema", according to one critic.<ref name="budd wilkins">{{cite web|last1=Wilkins|first1=Budd|title=The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeoisie-6699|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> For the first time, Bu√±uel made use of a [[video monitors|video-playback monitor]], which allowed him to make much more extensive use of [[crane shot]]s and elaborate [[tracking shot]]s, and enabled him to cut the film in the camera and eliminate the need for [[Re-shoot|reshoots]].<ref name=pinkos /> Filming required only two months and Bu√±uel claimed that editing took only one day.<ref name=pinkos /> When the film was released, Silberman decided to skip the Cannes Festival in order to concentrate on getting it nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]], which it won, leading Bu√±uel to express his contempt for a process that relied on the judgment of, "2500 idiots, including for example the assistant dress designer of the studio."<ref name=pinkos />
As was his habit, Bu√±uel took advantage of the popular success of ''Discreet Charm'' to make one of the "puzzling, idiosyncratic films he ''really'' wanted to make".<ref name="Polizzotti milky way" /> In 1973, at the [[Monastery of El Paular|Monastery of Paular]] in the Spanish [[Somosierra]], he wrote the screenplay for ''[[The Phantom of Liberty]]''(1974) with Carri√®re for production by Silberman and his Hollywood partners.<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.249}} The resulting film is a series of 12 distinctive episodes with separate protagonists, linked together only by following a character from one episode to another in a relay-race manner.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lanzagorta|first1=Marco|title=The Phantom of Liberty| url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2002/cteq/phantom/|website=Senses of Cinema|publisher=Film Victoria, Australia|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> Bu√±uel has stated that he made the film as a tribute to poet [[Benjamin P√©ret]], a founding member of French Surrealism,<ref name="bill krohn" />{{rp|p.170}} and called it his "most Surrealist film".<ref name=aranda />{{rp|p.249}}
Bu√±uel's final film was ''[[That Obscure Object of Desire]]'' (1977), adapted by Bu√±uel and Carri√®re from an 1898 novel by [[Pierre Lou√øs]] called ''[[La Femme et le pantin]]'', which had already been used as the basis of films directed by [[Josef von Sternberg]] ([[The Devil is a Woman (1935 film)|''The Devil is a Woman'']], 1935) and [[Julien Duvivier]] (''[[La Femme et le Pantin]]'', 1959). The film, which tells the story of an older man who is obsessed by a young woman who continually evades his attempts to consummate a sexual relationship, starred the Spanish actor [[Fernando Rey]], appearing in his fourth Bu√±uel film. Initially, the part of the young woman was to be played by [[Maria Schneider (actress)|Maria Schneider]], who had achieved international fame for her roles in ''[[Last Tango in Paris]]'' and [[The Passenger (1975 film)|''The Passenger'']],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grimes|first1=William|title=Maria Schneider, Actress in ''Last Tango'', Dies at 58|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/04/movies/04schneider.html|accessdate=16 December 2014|work=New York Times|date=4 February 2011}}</ref> but once shooting started, according to Carri√®re, her drug usage resulted in a "lackluster and dull" performance that caused tempestuous arguments with Bu√±uel on the set and her eventual dismissal.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Thomson|first1=David|title=David Thomson on Films: Remembering Maria Schneider|journal=New Republic|date=8 February 2011|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/books-and-arts/82975/david-thomson-films-remembering-maria-schneider|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref> Serge Silberman, the producer, decided to abandon the project at that point, but was convinced by Bu√±uel to continue shooting with two different actresses, [[Angela Molina]] and [[Carole Bouquet]] playing the same role in alternating sequences throughout the film. In his autobiography, Bu√±uel claimed that this unusual casting decision was his own idea after drinking two dry martinis, saying: "If I had to list all the benefits derived from alcohol, it would be endless".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pinkos|first1=Jefferey|title=Bu√±uel's Pursuit of That Obscure Object|url=http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/that-obscure-object-of-desire/|website=Lone Star Film Society|accessdate=17 December 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223155848/http://lonestarfilmsociety.com/that-obscure-object-of-desire/|archivedate=23 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Others have reported that Carri√®re had first broached the idea while developing the film's scenario, but had been brushed off by Bu√±uel as "the whim of a rainy day."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gonzalez|first1=Ed|title=That Obscure Object of Desire|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/that-obscure-object-of-desire|website=Slant Magazine|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref>
===Last years (1978‚Äì1983)=== {{quote box|bgcolor=#CCDDFF|align=right|width=25%|quote="Luis waited for death for a long time, like a good Spaniard, and when he died he was ready. His relationship with death was like that one has with a woman. He felt the love, hate, tenderness, ironical detachment of a long relationship, and he didn't want to miss the last encounter, the moment of union. "I hope I will die alive," he told me. At the end it was as he had wished. His last words were 'I'm dying'."<ref name="carriere flickhead" /> |source=Long-time friend and collaborator, [[Jean-Claude Carri√®re]]}} After the release of ''[[That Obscure Object of Desire]]'', Bu√±uel retired from filmmaking. In 1982, he wrote (along with Carri√®re) his autobiography, ''Mon Dernier Soupir'' (''My Last Sigh''), which provides an account of his life, friends, and family as well as a representation of his eccentric personality. In it, he recounts dreams, encounters with many well-known writers, actors, and artists such as [[Pablo Picasso]] and [[Charlie Chaplin]] as well as antics, like dressing up as a nun and walking around town.
In his seventies, Bu√±uel once told his friend, novelist [[Carlos Fuentes]]: "I'm not afraid of death. I'm afraid of dying alone in a hotel room, with my bags open and a shooting script on the night table. I must know whose fingers will close my eyes."<ref name="fuentes discreet charm">{{cite web|last1=Fuentes|first1=Carlos|title=The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeosie|url=http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/109-the-discreet-charm-of-the-bourgeosie|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> Bu√±uel died in Mexico City in 1983. Fuentes has recounted that Bu√±uel spent his last week in hospital discussing theology with the Jesuit brother Julian Pablo, a long time friend.<ref name="fuentes milky way">{{cite web|last1=Fuentes|first1=Carlos|title=The Milky Way: The Heretic's Progress|url=http://www.criterion.com/current/posts/610-the-milky-way-the-heretic-s-progress|website=Criterion Collection|accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref> His funeral was very private. There were about 50 people at the most, among them [[Octavio Paz]], [[Jos√© Luis Cuevas]], [[Miguel Littin]], his wife and two sons.
==Technique and influences== {{main|Filmmaking technique of Luis Bu√±uel}} [[File:SilviaPinalStatue.JPG|thumb|Silvia Pinal was one of Bu√±uel's "stock company" of actors and was his preferred choice for the lead in his film ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'', a part which finally went to [[Catherine Deneuve]]<ref name="faulkner literary adaptations">{{cite book|last1=Faulkner|first1=Sally|title=Literary Adaptations in Spanish Cinema|date=2004|publisher=Tamesis|location=London|isbn=978-1855660984|page=128|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yeMgJsea3-8C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage|accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref> ]] Bu√±uel's technique of filmmaking was strongly influenced by mise-en-scene, sound editing and use of music. The influences on his filmmaking have included a positive relationship to surrealism and a critical approach to atheism and religion. Bu√±uel's style of directing was extremely economical; he shot films in a few weeks, rarely deviating from his script (the scene in ''[[Tristana (film)|Tristana]]'' where [[Catherine Deneuve]] exposes her breasts to Saturno ‚Äì but not the audience ‚Äì being a noted exception) and shooting in order as much as possible to minimize editing time.<ref>{{cite book|last=Alexander|first=Sean|title="Luis Bu√±uel", in The Scarecrow Video Movie Guide|year=2004|publisher=Sasquatch Books|location=Seattle WA|isbn=978-1-57061-415-6|pages=31|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0qiQLs-6SocC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> He remained true throughout his working life to an operating philosophy that he articulated at the beginning of his career in 1928: "The guiding idea, the silent procession of images that are concrete, decisive, measured in space and time‚Äîin a word, the film‚Äîwas first projected inside the brain of the filmmaker".<ref name="an unspeakable betrayal" />{{rp|p.135}} In this, Bu√±uel has been compared with [[Alfred Hitchcock]], another director famous for precision, efficiency and preplanning, for whom actually shooting the film was an anticlimax, since each man would know, in Bu√±uel's words, "exactly how each scene will be shot and what the final montage will be".<ref>{{cite book|last=Stam|first=Robert|title="Hitchock and Bu√±uel: Authority, Desire and the Absurd", in Hitchcock's Rereleased Films: From Rope to Vertigo, ed. by Walter Raubicheck and Walter Srebnick|year=1991|publisher=Wayne State University Press|location=Detroit|isbn=978-0-8143-2326-7|pages=117|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CfVeQ5BaPVsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> According to actress [[Jeanne Moreau]]: "He was the only director I know who never threw away a shot. He had the film in his mind. When he said 'action' and 'cut,' you knew that what was in between the two would be printed."<ref name=yakir>{{cite web|last1=Yakir|first1=Dan|title=Two Old Masters: Luis Bu√±uel|url=http://www.filmcomment.com/article/luis-bunuel-remembered|website=Film Comment|publisher=Film Society of Lincoln Center|accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref>
==Tributes== [[File:Instituto IES Luis Bu√±uel.jpg|thumb|left|Instituto de Educaci√≥n Secundaria (IES) Luis Bu√±uel, Zaragoza, Spain]] * In 1994, a retrospective of Bu√±uel's works was organized by the [[Kunst- und Ausstellungshalle der Bundesrepublik Deutschland|Kunst- und Ausstellungshalle]] in Bonn, as homage to one of the most internationally revered figures in world cinema.<ref name="d'lugo">{{cite book|last=D'Lugo|first=Marvin|title="Bu√±uel in the Cathedral of Culture" in Marsha Kinder (ed.), Luis Bu√±uel's The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie|year=1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, New York|isbn=978-0-521-56831-9|pages=108}}</ref> {{rp|p.101}} This was followed in the summer of 1996 by a commemoration of the centenary of the birth of cinema held by the [[Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof√≠a]] in Madrid, which included a unique retrospective, jointly sponsored by the King of Spain and the President of Mexico, called ''¬øBu√±uel!. La mirada del siglo'', honoring his special status as Spanish cinema's most emblematic figure.<ref>{{cite web|title=¬øBu√±uel!. La mirada del siglo|url=http://www.museoreinasofia.es/publicaciones/catalogo.html?idPub=326|website=Cat√°logo de publicaciones|publisher=Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof√≠a|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> * A secondary school in [[Zaragoza]], Spain has been named for Bu√±uel: Instituto de Educaci√≥n Secundaria Ies Luis Bu√±uel.<ref>{{cite web|title=IES Luis Bu√±uel|url=http://iesluisbunuel.com/|publisher=http://iesluisbunuel.com/|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref> [[Liceo Espa√±ol Luis Bu√±uel]], a Spanish international school, is near Paris.<ref>{{cite web|title=Historia del Liceo Espa√±ol|url=http://www.educacion.gob.es/exterior/centros/luisbunuel/es/secretaria/historia.shtml|website=Liceo Espa√±ol Luis Bu√±uel|publisher=Gobierno de Espana. Ministerio de Educaci√≥n|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> * In [[Calanda, Spain]] a bust of the head of Luis Bu√±uel is on disp