==Characterizations== Bu√±uel has been portrayed as a character in many films and television productions. A portion of the television mini-series ''Lorca, muerte de un poeta'' (1987‚Äì1988), directed by [[Juan Antonio Bardem]] recreates the student years of Bu√±uel, Lorca and Dal√≠, with Fernando Valverde portraying Bu√±uel in two episodes.<ref>{{cite web|last=Selas|first=Alejandro Reche|title=La Hispalense rendir√° homenaje a Bu√±uel en marco del Festival de Cine|url=http://www.diariodesevilla.es/article/ocio/496982/la/hispalense/rendira/homenaje/bunuel/marco/festival/cine.html|website=Diario de Sevilla|publisher=[[Joly Digital]]|accessdate=7 August 2012}}</ref> He was played by Dimiter Guerasimof in the 1991 biopic ''Dal√≠'', directed by [[Antoni Ribas]], despite the fact that Dal√≠ and his attorney had written to Ribas objecting to the project in its early stages in 1985.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dal√≠ se opone a un proyecto de pel√≠cula de Antoni Ribas sobre el pintor|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1985/01/18/cultura/474850803_850215.html|accessdate=7 August 2012|newspaper=El Pais|date=18 January 1985}}</ref> Bu√±uel appeared as a character in Alejandro Pelayo's 1993 film ''Miroslava'', based on the life of actress [[Miroslava (actress)|Miroslava Stern]], who committed suicide after appearing in ''Ensayo de un crimen'' (1955).<ref>{{cite book|last=Montes Garces|first=Elizabeth|title=Relocating Identities in Latin American Cultures|year=2007|publisher=University of Calgary Press|location=Calgary|isbn=978-1-55238-209-7|pages=139‚Äì140|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l0KA5n4Gm9UC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> Bu√±uel was played by three actors, [[El Gran Wyoming]] (old age), Pere Arquillu√© (young adult) and Juan Carlos Jim√©nez Mar√≠n (child), in [[Carlos Saura]]'s 2001 fantasy, ''Bu√±uel y la mesa del rey Salom√≥n'', which tells of Bu√±uel, Lorca and Dal√≠ setting out in search of the mythical table of King Salom√≥n, which is thought to have the power to see into the past, the present and the future.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bu√±uel y la mesa del Rey Salom√≥n|url=http://www.clubcultura.com/clubcine/bunuel_saura/bunuel_saura1.htm|website=Noticias|publisher=ClubCine|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> Bu√±uel was a character in a 2001 television miniseries ''[[Severo Ochoa]]: La conquista de un Nobel'', on the life of the Spanish [[√©migr√©]] and [[Nobel Prize]] winner in medicine, who was also at the Residencia de Estudiantes during Bu√±uel's time there.<ref>{{cite web|title=Residencia de Estudiantes ‚Äì History|url=http://www.residencia.csic.es/en/info/history.htm|publisher=Residencia de Estudiantes|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> [[Matt Lucas]] portrayed Bu√±uel in Richard Curson Smith's 2002 TV movie ''Surrealissimo: The Scandalous Success of Salvador Dal√≠'', a comedy depicting Dal√≠'s "trial" by the Surrealists in 1934 for his pro-Hitler sympathies.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rojas|first=Carlos|title=Salvador Dal√≠, Or The Art of Spitting on Your Mother's Portrait|year=1993|publisher=Penn State Press|location=University Park PA|isbn=978-0-271-00842-4|pages=98|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MWF5s2yfFqwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}</ref> A 2005 short called ''[[The Death of Salvador Dali]]'', directed by Delaney Bishop, contains sequences in which Bu√±uel appears, played by Alejandro Cardenas.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Death of Salvador Dali ‚Äì Press release|url=http://www.dalimovie.com/Press.html|publisher=dalimovie.com|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> [[Paul Morrison (director)|Paul Morrison]]'s ''[[Little Ashes]]'' hypothesizes a love affair between Dal√≠ and Lorca, with Bu√±uel (played by [[Matthew McNulty]]) looking on suspiciously.<ref>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=David|title=Were Spain's two artistic legends secret gay lovers?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/oct/28/spain.books|accessdate=8 August 2012|newspaper=The Observer|date=27 October 2007|location=London}}</ref> Bu√±uel, played by Adrien de Va